# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: albion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was most recently revised for its ninth edition of 1940.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] Abridged versions and a supplement exist.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was initially the basis for the 2021 *Cambridge Greek Lexicon*, although subsequently that became a complete rewrite from scratch.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The lexicon was begun in the 19th century, and is now in its ninth (revised) edition, published in 1940.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was based on the earlier *Handwörterbuch der griechischen Sprache* by the German lexicographer Franz Passow (first published in 1819, fourth edition 1831), which in turn was based on Johann Gottlob Schneider's *Kritisches griechisch-deutsches Handwörterbuch*.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Lexicon* has served as the basis for all later lexicographical work on the ancient Greek language, such as the ongoing Greek–Spanish dictionary project *Diccionario Griego–Español* (DGE).
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is now conventionally referred to as *Liddell & Scott*, *Liddell–Scott–Jones*, or *LSJ*, and its three sizes are sometimes referred to as "The Little Liddell", "The Middle Liddell" and "The Big Liddell" or "The Great Scott".
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ main edition has 116,502 entries.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] According to Stuart Jones's preface to the ninth (1925) edition, the creation of the *Lexicon* was originally proposed by David Alphonso Talboys, an Oxford publisher.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] It was published by the Clarendon Press at Oxford rather than by Talboys, who died before the first edition (1843) was complete.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The first editor of the LSJ, Henry George Liddell, was Dean of Christ Church, Oxford, and the father of Alice Liddell, the eponymous Alice of the writings of Lewis Carroll.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The eighth edition (1897) was the last edition published during Liddell's lifetime.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ is sometimes compared and contrasted with *A Latin Dictionary* by Lewis and Short, which was also published by Oxford University Press (OUP).
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] It is also sometimes compared with the Bauer lexicon, which is a similar work focused on the Greek of the New Testament.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The LSJ's definitions reflect the Victorian morality of its time, using euphemism.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, χέζω (*chezo*, 'to shit'), is translated as "ease oneself, do one's need"; βινέω (*bineo*, 'to fuck') as "inire, coire, of illicit intercourse"; and λαικάζω (*laikazo*, 'to suck cocks') as "to wench".
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] Two condensed editions of LSJ were published by Oxford University Press and remain in print.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1843, the same year as the full lexicon's publication, *A Lexicon: Abridged from Liddell and Scott's Greek–English Lexicon*, sometimes called "the Little Liddell" was published.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] For example, a reprint, re-typeset in 2007, of the 1909 edition is available from Simon Wallenberg Press.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] In 1889, an intermediate edition of the lexicon, *An Intermediate Greek–English Lexicon*, was prepared on the basis of the seventh edition (1883) of LSJ.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] After the publication of the ninth edition in 1940, and shortly after the deaths of both Stuart Jones and McKenzie, the OUP maintained a list of *addenda et corrigenda* ("additions and corrections"), which was bound with subsequent printings.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] However, in 1968, these were replaced by a Supplement to the LSJ.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] Neither the *addenda* nor the Supplement has ever been merged into the main text, which still stands as originally composed by Liddell, Scott, Jones, and McKenzie.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement was initially edited by M.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] Glare, editor of the *Oxford Latin Dictionary* (not to be confused with Lewis and Short's *A Latin Dictionary*).
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] Since 1988, it has been edited by Glare and Anne A.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] As the title page of the *Lexicon* makes clear (and the prefaces to the main text and to the Supplement attest), this editorial work has been performed "with the cooperation of many scholars".
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Supplement primarily takes the form of a list of additions and corrections to the main text, sorted by entry.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The supplemental entries are marked with signs to show the nature of the changes they call for.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] Thus, a user of the *Lexicon* can consult the Supplement after consulting the main text to see whether scholarship after Jones and McKenzie has provided any new information about a particular word.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] As of 2005, the most recent revision of the Supplement, published in 1996, contains 320 pages of corrections to the main text, as well as other materials.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The small "x" indicates that this word did not appear in the main text at all; "S.*fr*." refers to the collected fragmentary works of Sophocles.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] One interesting new source of lexicographic material in the revised Supplement is the Mycenean inscriptions.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The ninth edition of LSJ has been freely available in electronic form since 2007, having been digitized by the Perseus Project.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] Diogenes, a free software package, incorporates the Perseus data and allows easy offline consultation of LSJ on Mac OS X, Windows, and Linux platforms.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] Marcion is another open source application that includes the Perseus LSJ.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] For mobile devices, both the Kindle E-Ink and the iPhone/iPod Touch feature data ported from Perseus.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Android market also currently offers the intermediate LSJ as an offline downloadable app for free or for a small price.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] A CD-ROM version published and sold by Logos Bible Software also incorporates the Supplement's additions to the ninth edition of LSJ.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] A new online version of LSJ was released in 2011 by the Thesaurus Linguae Graecae (TLG).
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The TLG version corrects "a large number of typographical errors", and includes links to the extensive TLG textual corpus.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] A Kindle version, the "Complete Liddell & Scott's Lexicon with Inflections", is also available: it allows searches of most Classical Greek word-forms and supports a growing number of Ancient/Classical Greek texts for the device.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The Lexicon has been translated into Modern Greek by Xenophon Moschos, ed.: Michael Konstantinidis and was published by Anestis Konstantinidis in 1904 with the title *H.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] Scott – Α.* Κωνσταντινίδου (Μέγα Λεξικόν τῆς Ἑλληνικῆς Γλώσσης).
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] Also, a supplement compiled by a group of Greek philologists.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] An Italian translation of the *Intermediate Liddell-Scott*, entitled *Dizionario illustrato Greco-Italiano* was published in 1975 by Le Monnier, edited by Q.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] LSJ was the basis of the project of John Chadwick and James Diggle at Cambridge to publish the *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* of 2021.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] Although it was initially conceived as a mere update of LSJ, the editors eventually decided to start afresh since they considered LSJ "too antiquated in concept, design and content".
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The CGL has a smaller scope than the LSJ (and also the *Brill Dictionary of Ancient Greek*), and is unlikely to replace it; however, it is still more comprehensive than the Middle Liddell, which it intends to replace.
[src:albion/a-greek-english-lexicon] The *Cambridge Greek Lexicon* uses contemporary language for its definitions and, unlike the LSJ, no longer elides the meaning of words considered offensive in Victorian times.
[src:albion/alan-rayburn] After earning a degree in geography, he joined the Geographical Branch of the Federal Department of Mines and Technical Survey in 1957, where he worked on the creation of a Canadian atlas.
[src:albion/alan-rayburn] He was appointed as the first official toponymic researcher in Canada in 1967, and was among the charter members of the Ontario Geographic Names Board and the Toponymic Division of the Canadian Permanent Committee on Geographic Names.
[src:albion/alan-rayburn] From 1979 to 1982, Rayburn served as the president of the Canadian Society for the Study of Names.
[src:albion/alan-rayburn] Recognized as an authority on North American toponymy, Rayburn wrote over 100 articles and eight books across his career.
[src:albion/alan-rayburn] He wrote extensively for *Canadian Geographic*, and published several scholarly works in *Names: A Journal of Onomastics*.
[src:albion/alan-rayburn] Rayburn died on 26 September 2019 in Ontario, at the age of 86.
[src:albion/alba] The term first appears in classical texts as Ἀλβίων **Albíōn** or Ἀλουΐων **Alouíōn** (in Ptolemy's writings in Greek), and later as **Albion** in Latin documents.
[src:albion/alba] Historically, the term refers to Britain as a whole and is ultimately based on the Indo-European root for "white".
[src:albion/alba] It later came to be used by Gaelic speakers in the form of **Alba** (dative **Albainn**, genitive **Albann**, now obsolete) as the name given to the former kingdom of the Picts which, when first used in this sense (around the time of king Causantín mac Áeda (Constantine II, 943–952)), had expanded.
[src:albion/alba] The region of Breadalbane (**Bràghad Albann**, the upper part of "Alba") takes its name from it as well.
[src:albion/alba] As time passed, that kingdom incorporated other territories to its south.
[src:albion/alba] It became re-Latinised in the High Medieval period as "Albania" (it is unclear whether it may ultimately share the same etymon as the modern Albania).
[src:albion/alba] This latter word was employed mainly by Celto-Latin writers, and most famously by Geoffrey of Monmouth.
[src:albion/alba] It was this word which passed into Middle English as Albany, although very rarely was this used for the Kingdom of Scotland, but rather for the notional Duchy of Albany.
[src:albion/alba] It is from the latter that Albany, the capital of the US state of New York, and Albany, Western Australia, take their names.
[src:albion/alba] BBC Alba, a television channel broadcasting mainly in Scottish Gaelic, was launched in September 2008 as a joint venture between the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) and Gaelic company MG Alba.
[src:albion/alba] A new version of Runrig's song *Alba* (originally on their album, *The Cutter and the Clan*) was featured on the channel's launch.
[src:albion/alba] In the mid-1990s, the Celtic League started a campaign to have the word "Alba" on the Scottish football and rugby tops.
[src:albion/alba] Since 2005, the SFA have supported the use of Scottish Gaelic by adding *Alba* on the back of the official team strip.
[src:albion/alba] However, as of 2008, the SRU is still being lobbied to have *Alba* added to the national rugby union strip.
[src:albion/alba] In 2007, the then Scottish Executive re-branded itself as "The Scottish Government" and started to use a bilingual logo with the Gaelic name *Riaghaltas na h-Alba*.
[src:albion/alba] However, the Gaelic version from the outset had always been *Riaghaltas na h-Alba*.
[src:albion/alba] The Scottish Parliament, likewise, uses the Gaelic name *Pàrlamaid na h-Alba*.
[src:albion/alba] A new welcome sign on the historic A7 route into Scotland was erected in 2009, with the text *Fàilte gu Alba*.
[src:albion/alba] Phrases such as *Alba gu bràth* may be used as a catch-phrase or rallying cry.
[src:albion/alba] It was used in the movie *Braveheart* as William Wallace encouraged the troops at the Battle of Stirling Bridge.
[src:albion/alba] In March 2021, former first minister of Scotland and leader of the SNP Alex Salmond launched the pro-independence Alba Party, set to contest the 2021 Scottish Parliament elections.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Albania was inhabited by several Illyrian tribes, among them the Ardiaei, Bylliones, Dassaretii, Enchele, and Taulantians, with the Chaonians settled in the southwest.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Several colonies were founded by the Ancient Greeks along the Albanian coast, most notably Apollonia.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Illyrians were the dominant power in Albania before the rise of Macedon.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Following the Illyrian Wars, Albania was integrated into the Roman Empire and remained in the Byzantine Empire after its partition.
[src:albion/albania-p01] During the Middle Ages, several Albanian principalities emerged, most notably the Principality of Arbanon, Kingdom of Albania, Principality of Albania and Albania Veneta.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In the 15th century, Albania became a center of resistance against Ottoman expansion under the leadership of Gjergj Kastrioti Skanderbeg, whose military campaigns repelled Ottoman advances for over two decades.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Although incorporated into the Ottoman Empire, Albania retained distinct cultural and social identities throughout four centuries of foreign rule, culminating in the Albanian Renaissance in the 19th century.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Albania declared independence in 1912, followed by a turbulent 20th century marked by monarchy, foreign occupation during both World Wars, and a communist regime under Enver Hoxha.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Since its independence in 1912, Albania has undergone a number of political changes, transitioning from a monarchy to a communist regime before becoming a sovereign parliamentary constitutional republic.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Governed by a constitution prioritising the separation of powers, the country's political structure includes a parliament, a ceremonial president, a functional prime minister and a hierarchy of courts.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Albania is a developing country with an upper-middle income economy driven by the service sector, with manufacturing and tourism, which attracted over 11 million visitors in 2024, also playing significant roles.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The illegal drug trade in Albania contributes around US$100 million to the economy per year.
[src:albion/albania-p01] After the dissolution of its communist system, the country shifted from centralised planning to an open market economy.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Albanian citizens have universal health care access and free primary and secondary education.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The country is an official candidate for membership in the European Union, and has been negotiating accession since 2022.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The origin of the name "Albania" can be traced back to medieval Latin and the association with the Illyrian tribe of the Albani.
[src:albion/albania-p01] This connection is further supported by the writings of the Ancient Greek geographer Ptolemy during the 2nd century AD, where he included the settlement of Albanopolis situated to the northeast of Durrës.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The presence of a medieval settlement named Albanon or Arbanon hints at the possibility of historical continuity.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The precise relationship between these historical references and the question of whether Albanopolis was synonymous with Albanon remain subjects of scholarly debate.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Byzantine historian Michael Attaliates, in his 11th-century historical account, provides the earliest undisputed reference to the Albanians, when he mentions them as participants in a revolt against Constantinople in 1079.
[src:albion/albania-p01] He also identifies the Arbanitai as subjects of the Duke of Dyrrachium.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In the Middle Ages, Albania was denoted as *Arbëri* or *Arbëni* by its inhabitants, who identified themselves as *Arbëreshë* or *Arbëneshë*.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Albanians employ the terms *Shqipëri* or *Shqipëria* for their nation, designations that trace their historical origins to the 14th century.
[src:albion/albania-p01] But only in the late 17th and early 18th centuries did these terms gradually supersede *Arbëria* and *Arbëreshë* among Albanians.
[src:albion/albania-p01] These two expressions are widely interpreted to symbolise "Children of the Eagles" and "Land of the Eagles".
[src:albion/albania-p01] Mesolithic habitation in Albania has been evidenced in several open-air sites which were close to the Adriatic coastline and in caves.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Mesolithic objects found in a cave near Xarrë include flint and jasper objects along with fossilised animal bones, while those discoveries at Mount Dajt comprise bone and stone tools similar to those of the Aurignacian culture.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Neolithic era in Albania began around 7000 BC and is evidenced in finds which indicate domestication of sheep and goats and small-scale agriculture.
[src:albion/albania-p01] A part of the Neolithic population may have been the same as the Mesolithic population of the southern Balkans, like in the Konispol cave, where the Mesolithic stratum co-exists with Pre-Pottery Neolithic finds.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Cardium pottery culture appears in coastal Albania and across the Adriatic after 6500 BC, while the settlements of the interior took part in the processes that formed the Starčevo culture.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Albanian bitumen mines of Selenicë provide early evidence of bitumen exploitation in Europe, dating to Late Neolithic Albania (from 5000 BC), when local communities used it as pigment for ceramic decoration, waterproofing, and adhesive for repairing broken vessels.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The bitumen of Selenicë circulated towards eastern Albania from the early 5th millennium BC.
[src:albion/albania-p01] First evidence of its overseas trade export comes from the Neolithic and Bronze Age southern Italy.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The high-quality bitumen of Selenicë has been exploited throughout all the historical ages since the Late Neolithic era until today.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Indo-Europeanisation of Albania in the context of the IE-isation of the western Balkans began after 2800 BC.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The presence of the Early Bronze Age tumuli in the vicinity of later Apollonia dates to 2679±174 calBC (2852–2505 calBC).
[src:albion/albania-p01] These burial mounds belong to the southern expression of the Adriatic-Ljubljana culture (related to the later Cetina culture), which moved southwards along the Adriatic from the northern Balkans.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The same community built similar mounds in Montenegro (Rakića Kuće) and northern Albania (Shtoj).
[src:albion/albania-p01] The first archaeogenetic find related to the IE-isation of Albania involves a man with predominantly Yamnaya ancestry buried in a tumulus of northeastern Albania, which dates to 2663–2472 calBC.
[src:albion/albania-p01] During the Middle Bronze Age, Cetina culture sites and finds appear in Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Cetina culture moved southwards across the Adriatic from the Cetina valley of Dalmatia.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The incorporated territory of Albania was historically inhabited by Indo-European peoples, amongst them numerous Illyrian and Epirote tribes.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The territory referred to as Illyria corresponded roughly to the area east of the Adriatic Sea in the Mediterranean Sea, extending in the south to the mouth of the Vjosë.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The first account of the Illyrian groups comes from the Periplus of the Euxine Sea, a Greek text written in the 4th century BC.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Bryges were also present in central Albania, while the south was inhabited by the Epirote Chaonians, whose capital was at Phoenice.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Other colonies, such as Apollonia and Epidamnos, were established by Greek city-states on the coast by the 7th century BC.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Illyrian Taulanti were a powerful Illyrian tribe among the earliest recorded tribes in the area.
[src:albion/albania-p01] They lived in an area that corresponds with much of present-day Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Together with the Dardanian ruler Cleitus, Glaucias, the ruler of the Taulantian kingdom, fought against Alexander the Great at the Battle of Pelium in 335 BC.
[src:albion/albania-p01] As time passed, the ruler of Ancient Macedonia, Cassander of Macedon, captured Apollonia and crossed the river Genusus (Albanian: *Shkumbin*) in 314 BC.
[src:albion/albania-p01] A few years later, Glaucias laid siege to Apollonia and captured the Greek colony of Epidamnos.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Illyrian Ardiaei tribe, centred in Montenegro, ruled over most of the territory of northern Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Their Ardiaean Kingdom reached its greatest extent under King Agron, the son of Pleuratus II.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Agron extended his rule over other neighbouring tribes as well.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Following Agron's death in 230 BC, his wife, Teuta, inherited the Ardiaean kingdom.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Teuta's forces extended their operations further southwards to the Ionian Sea.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In 229 BC, Rome declared war on the kingdom for extensively plundering Roman ships.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The war ended in an Illyrian defeat in 227 BC.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Teuta was eventually succeeded by Gentius in 181 BC.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Gentius clashed with the Romans in 168 BC, initiating the Third Illyrian War.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The conflict resulted in the Roman conquest of the region by 167 BC.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Romans split the region into three administrative divisions.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Roman Empire was split in 395 upon the death of Theodosius I into an Eastern and Western Roman Empire, in part because of the increasing pressure from threats during the Barbarian Invasions.
[src:albion/albania-p01] From the 6th century into the 7th century, the Slavs crossed the Danube and largely absorbed the indigenous Greeks, Illyrians, and Thracians in the Balkans; thus, the Illyrians were mentioned for the last time in historical records in the 7th century.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In the 11th century, the Great Schism formalised the break of communion between the Eastern Orthodox and Western Catholic Church, which is reflected in Albania through the emergence of a Catholic north and Orthodox south.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Albanian people inhabited the west of Lake Ochrida and the upper valley of the River Shkumbin and established the Principality of Arbanon in 1190 under the leadership of Progon of Kruja.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The realm was succeeded by his sons Gjin Progoni and Demetrio Progoni.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Upon the death of Dhimiter, the territory came under the rule of the Albanian-Greek Gregorios Kamonas and subsequently under the Golem of Kruja.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In the 13th century, the principality was dissolved.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Arbanon is considered to be the first sketch of an Albanian state, which retained a semi-autonomous status as the western extremity of the Byzantine Empire, under the Byzantine Doukai of Epirus or Laskarids of Nicaea.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Towards the end of the 12th and beginning of the 13th centuries, Serbs and Venetians began to take possession of the territory.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The ethnogenesis of the Albanians is uncertain; however, the first undisputed mention of Albanians dates back in historical records from 1079 or 1080 in a work by Michael Attaleiates, who referred to the Albanoi as having taken part in a revolt against Constantinople.
[src:albion/albania-p01] At this point, the Albanians were fully Christianised.
[src:albion/albania-p01] After the dissolution of Arbanon, Charles I of Anjou concluded an agreement with the Albanian rulers, promising to protect them and their ancient liberties.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In 1272, he established the Kingdom of Albania and conquered regions back from the Despotate of Epirus.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The kingdom claimed all of central Albania territory from Dyrrhachium along the Adriatic Sea coast down to Butrint.
[src:albion/albania-p01] A Catholic political structure was a basis for the papal plans of spreading Catholicism in the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:albion/albania-p01] This plan also found the support of Helen of Anjou.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Around 30 Catholic churches and monasteries were built during her rule, mainly in northern Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Internal power struggles within the Byzantine Empire in the 14th century enabled Serbs' most powerful medieval ruler, Stefan Dušan, to establish a short-lived empire that included all of Albania except Durrës.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In 1367, Albanian rulers established the Despotate of Arta.
[src:albion/albania-p01] During that time, several Albanian principalities were established, notably the Principality of Albania, the Principality of Kastrioti, the Lordship of Berat, and the Principality of Dukagjini.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In the first half of the 15th century, the Ottoman Empire invaded most of Albania, and the League of Lezhë was organized under Skanderbeg as a ruler, who became the national hero of the Albanian medieval history.
[src:albion/albania-p01] that halted Ottoman advance into Europe for 25 years.
[src:albion/albania-p01] With the fall of Constantinople, the Ottoman Empire entered an extended period of military conquest and expansion, with its borders gradually expanding deep into Southeast Europe.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In 1385, they reached the Albanian Ionian Sea Coast, while in 1415, they established their garrisons across Southern Albania, eventually occupying most of Albania in 1431.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Thousands of Albanians consequently fled to Western Europe, particularly to Calabria, Naples, Ragusa, and Sicily, while numerous others sought protection at the often inaccessible Mountains of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Since the vast majority of Albanians were adherents of Christianity, they were considered an inferior class of people, resulting in them being discriminated against in various forms, including being subjected to heavy taxes.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Additionally, the Devshirme system allowed the Sultan to collect a requisite percentage of Christian adolescents from their families to compose the Janissary.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Ottoman conquest was also accompanied by the gradual process of Islamisation and the rapid construction of mosques.
[src:albion/albania-p01] A prosperous and longstanding revolution erupted after the formation of the League of Lezhë until the fall of Shkodër under the leadership of Gjergj Kastrioti Skanderbeg, who consistently defeated major Ottoman armies led by Sultans Murad II and Mehmed II.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Skanderbeg managed to unite several of the Albanian principalities, amongst them the Arianitis, Dukagjinis, Zaharias, and Thopias, and establish a centralised authority over most of the non-conquered territories, becoming the Lord of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Despite his competence as a military leader, Skanderbeg's victories over the Ottoman Empire's military had only a short-term impact, as his forces were unable to halt the Ottomans' advancement permanently; therefore, they successfully delayed the final conquest of Albanian lands only temporarily.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The constant Ottoman invasions caused enormous destruction to Albania, greatly reducing the population and destroying flocks of livestock and crops.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Besides surrender, there was no possible way Skanderbeg would be able to halt the Ottoman invasions despite his military forces achieving several consecutive victories against them.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Among other factors, his manpower and resources were insufficient for a prolonged war, preventing him from expanding the war efforts and driving the Turks from the Albanian borders.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Albania was therefore doomed to face an unending series of Ottoman attacks until it eventually fell years after his death.
[src:albion/albania-p01] When the Ottomans were gaining a firm foothold in the region, Albanian towns were organised into four principal sanjaks.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The government fostered trade by settling a sizeable Jewish colony of refugees fleeing persecution in Spain.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The city of Vlorë saw passing through its ports imported merchandise from Europe, such as velvets, cotton goods, mohairs, carpets, spices, and leather from Bursa and Constantinople.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Some citizens of Vlorë even had business associates throughout Europe.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The phenomenon of Islamisation among the Albanians became primarily widespread from the 17th century and continued into the 18th century.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Islam offered them equal opportunities and advancement within the Ottoman Empire.
[src:albion/albania-p01] However, according to some scholars, motives for conversion were diverse depending on the context; although the lack of source material significantly hampers efforts to investigate such issues.
[src:albion/albania-p01] As a result of the Ottomans' increasing suppression of Catholicism, most Catholic Albanians converted in the 17th century, while Orthodox Albanians followed suit mainly in the following century.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Since the Albanian-inhabited regions were considered strategically important, Albanians made up a significant proportion of the Ottoman Empire's military and bureaucracy.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Consequently, many Muslim Albanians attained important political and military positions, while their work made a significant cultural contribution to the broader Muslim world.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Enjoying this privileged position, they held various high administrative positions, which, among others, included over two dozen Albanians serving as Grand viziers of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Additionally, other distinguished Albanians included members of the prominent Köprülü family, Zagan Pasha, Muhammad Ali of Egypt, and Ali Pasha of Tepelena.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Furthermore, two Ottoman sultans, Bayezid II and Mehmed III, were born to mothers of Albanian ethnic backgrounds.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Albanian Renaissance was a period with its roots in the late 18th century and continuing into the 19th century, during which the Albanian people gathered spiritual and intellectual strength for an independent cultural and political life within an independent nation.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Modern Albanian culture flourished too, especially Albanian literature and arts, and was frequently linked to the influences of the Romanticism and Enlightenment principles.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Prior to the rise of nationalism, Ottoman authorities suppressed any expression of national unity or conscience by the Albanian people.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The victory of Russia over the Ottoman Empire following the Russian-Ottoman Wars resulted the execution of the Treaty of San Stefano which assigned Albanian-populated lands to their Slavic and Greek neighbours.
[src:albion/albania-p01] However, the United Kingdom and Austro-Hungarian Empire consequently blocked the arrangement and caused the Treaty of Berlin.
[src:albion/albania-p01] From this point, Albanians started to organise themselves with the goal to protect and unite the Albanian-populated lands into a unitary nation, leading to the formation of the League of Prizren.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The league had initially the assistance of the Ottoman authorities whose position was based on the religious solidarity of Muslim people and landlords connected with the Ottoman administration.
[src:albion/albania-p01] They favoured and protected the Muslim solidarity and called for defence of Muslim lands simultaneously constituting the reason for titling the league Committee of the Real Muslims.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Approximately 300 Muslims participated in the assembly composed by delegates from Bosnia, the administrator of the Sanjak of Prizren as representatives of the central authorities and no delegates from Vilayet of Scutari.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Ottomans authorities cancelled their assistance when the league, under Abdyl Frashëri, became focused on working towards Albanian autonomy and requested merging four vilayets, including Kosovo, Shkodër, Monastir and Ioannina, into a unified vilayet, the Albanian Vilayet.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The league used military force to prevent the annexing areas of Plav and Gusinje assigned to Montenegro.
[src:albion/albania-p01] After several successful battles with Montenegrin troops, such as the Battle of Novšiće, the league was forced to retreat from their contested regions.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The league was later defeated by the Ottoman army sent by the sultan.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Albania declared independence from the Ottoman Empire on 28 November 1912, accompanied by the establishment of the Senate and Government by the Assembly of Vlorë on 4 December 1912.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Its sovereignty was recognised by the Conference of London.
[src:albion/albania-p01] On 29 July 1913, the Treaty of London delineated the borders of the country and its neighbors, leaving many Albanians outside Albania, predominantly partitioned between Montenegro, Serbia, and Greece.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Headquartered in Vlorë, the International Commission of Control was established on 15 October 1913 to take care of the administration of Albania until its own political institutions were in order.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The International Gendarmerie was established as the Principality of Albania's first law enforcement agency.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In November, the first gendarmerie members arrived in the country.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Prince of Albania Wilhelm of Wied *(Princ Vilhelm Vidi)* was selected as the first prince of the principality.
[src:albion/albania-p01] On 7 March, he arrived in the provisional capital of Durrës and began to organise his government, appointing Turhan Pasha Përmeti to form the first Albanian cabinet.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In November 1913, the Albanian pro-Ottoman forces had offered the throne of Albania to the Ottoman war minister of Albanian origin, Ahmed Izzet Pasha.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The pro-Ottoman peasants believed that the new regime was a tool of the six Christian Great Powers and local landowners, who owned half of the arable land.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In February 1914, the Autonomous Republic of Northern Epirus was proclaimed in Gjirokastër by the local Greek population against incorporation to Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p01] This initiative was short-lived, and in 1921 the southern provinces were incorporated into the Albanian Principality.
[src:albion/albania-p01] High-ranking Orthodox clergy were among the strongest opponents of the Albanian National Awakening.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Reports from the period, including those from international observers, documented the burning of villages and civilian casualties.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Nationalist Orthodox insurgents were accused of targeting Muslim Albanian populations to consolidate territorial claims for Greece.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Meanwhile, the revolt of Albanian peasants against the new regime erupted under the leadership of the group of Muslim clerics gathered around Essad Pasha Toptani, who proclaimed himself the savior of Albania and Islam.
[src:albion/albania-p01] To gain the support of the Mirdita Catholic volunteers from northern Albania, Prince Wied appointed their leader, Prênk Bibë Doda, foreign minister of the Principality of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In May and June 1914, the International Gendarmerie was joined by Isa Boletini and his men, mostly from Kosovo, and the rebels defeated northern Mirdita Catholics, capturing most of Central Albania by the end of August 1914.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Prince Wied's regime collapsed, and he left the country on 3 September 1914.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The interwar period in Albania was marked by persistent economic and social difficulties, political instability and foreign interventions.
[src:albion/albania-p01] After World War I, Albania lacked an established government and internationally recognised borders, rendering it vulnerable to neighboring entities such as Greece, Italy, and Yugoslavia, all of which sought to expand their influence.
[src:albion/albania-p01] This led to political uncertainty, highlighted in 1918 when the Congress of Durrës sought Paris Peace Conference protection but was denied, further complicating Albania's position on the international stage.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Territorial tensions escalated as Yugoslavia, particularly Serbia, sought control of northern Albania, while Greece aimed dominance in southern Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The situation deteriorated in 1919 when the Serbs launched attacks on Albanian inhabitants, among others in Gusinje and Plav, resulting in massacres and large-scale displacement.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Meanwhile, Italian influence continued to expand during this time, driven by economic interests and political ambitions.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Fan Noli, renowned for his idealism, became prime minister in 1924, with a vision to institute a Western-style constitutional government, abolish feudalism, counter Italian influence, and enhance critical sectors, including infrastructure, education and healthcare.
[src:albion/albania-p01] He faced resistance from former allies, who had assisted in the removal of Zog from power, and struggled to secure foreign aid to implement his agenda.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Noli's decision to establish diplomatic ties with the Soviet Union, an adversary of the Serbian elite, ignited allegations of bolshevism from Belgrade.
[src:albion/albania-p01] This in turn led to increased pressure from Italy and culminated in Zog's restoration to authority.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In 1928, Zog transitioned Albania from a republic to a monarchy that garnered backing from Fascist Italy, with Zog assuming the title of King Zog I.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Key constitutional changes dissolved the Senate and established a unicameral National Assembly while preserving Zog's authoritative powers.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In 1939, Italy under Benito Mussolini launched a military invasion of Albania, resulting in the exile of Zog and the creation of an Italian protectorate.
[src:albion/albania-p01] As World War II progressed, Italy aimed to expand its territorial dominion in the Balkans, including territorial claims on regions of Greece (Chameria), Macedonia, Montenegro and Kosovo.
[src:albion/albania-p01] These ambitions laid the foundation of Greater Albania, which aimed to unite all areas with Albanian-majority populations into a single country.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In 1943, as Italy's control declined, Nazi Germany assumed control of Albania, subjecting Albanians to forced labour, economic exploitation and repression under German rule.
[src:albion/albania-p01] This period saw the forced expulsion and massacres of the Cham Albanians, a predominantly Muslim group.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The religious divide was used as a justification for violence, with some Orthodox locals reportedly identifying Muslim neighbors to paramilitary groups, leading to massacres and the forced expulsion of thousands.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The tide shifted in 1944 when Albanian partisan forces, under the leadership of Enver Hoxha and other communist leaders, successfully liberated Albania from German occupation.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The establishment of the People's Republic of Albania under the leadership of Enver Hoxha was a significant epoch in modern Albanian history.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Hoxha's regime embraced Marxist–Leninist ideologies and implemented authoritarian policies, including prohibition of religious practices, severe restrictions on travel, and abolition of private property rights.
[src:albion/albania-p01] It was also defined by a persistent pattern of purges, extensive repression, instances of betrayal, and hostility to external influences.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Any form of opposition or resistance to his rule was met with expeditious and severe consequences, such as internal exile, extended imprisonment, and execution.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The regime confronted a multitude of challenges, including widespread poverty, illiteracy, health crises and gender inequality.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In response, Hoxha initiated a modernisation initiative aimed at attaining economic and social liberation and transforming Albania into an industrial society.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Albania's diplomatic history under Hoxha was characterised by notable conflicts.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Initially aligned with Yugoslavia as a satellite state, the relationship deteriorated as Yugoslavia aimed to incorporate Albania within its territory.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Subsequently, Albania established relations with the Soviet Union and engaged trade agreements with other Eastern European countries, but experienced disagreements over Soviet policies, leading to strained ties with Moscow and diplomatic separation in 1961.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Simultaneously, tensions with the West heightened due to Albania's refusal to hold free elections and allegations of Western support for anti-communist uprisings.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Albania's enduring partnership was with China; it sided with Beijing during the Sino-Soviet conflict, resulting in severed ties with the Soviet Union and withdrawal from the Warsaw Pact in response to the invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968.
[src:albion/albania-p01] But their relations stagnated in 1970, prompting both to reassess their commitment, and Albania actively reduced its dependence on China.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Under Hoxha's regime, Albania underwent a widespread campaign targeting religious clergy of various faiths, resulting in public persecution and executions, particularly targeting Muslims, Roman Catholics and Eastern Orthodox adherents.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In 1946, religious estates underwent nationalisation, coinciding with the closure or transformation of religious institutions into various other purposes.
[src:albion/albania-p01] This culminated in 1976, when Albania became the world's first constitutionally atheist state.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Under this regime, citizens were forced to renounce their religious beliefs, adopt a secular way of life, and embrace socialist ideology.
[src:albion/albania-p01] After four decades of communism paired with the revolutions of 1989, Albania witnessed a notable rise in political activism, particularly among students, which led to a transformation in the prevailing order.
[src:albion/albania-p01] After the first multi-party elections of 1991, the communist party maintained a stronghold in the parliament until its defeat in the parliamentary elections of 1992 directed by the Democratic Party.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Considerable economic and financial resources were devoted to pyramid schemes that were widely supported by the government.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The schemes swept up somewhere between one sixth and one third of the population of the country.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Despite the International Monetary Fund's warnings, Sali Berisha defended the schemes as large investment firms, leading more people to redirect their remittances and sell their homes and cattle for cash to deposit in the schemes.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The schemes began to collapse in late 1996, leading many of the investors to join initially peaceful protests against the government, requesting their money back.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The protests turned violent in February 1997 as government forces responded by firing on the demonstrators.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In March, the Police and Republican Guard deserted, leaving their armories open.
[src:albion/albania-p01] These were promptly emptied by militias and criminal gangs.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The resulting civil war caused a wave of evacuations of foreign nationals and refugees.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The crisis led both Aleksandër Meksi and Sali Berisha to resign from office in the wake of the general election.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In April 1997, Operation Alba, a U.N. peacekeeping force led by Italy, entered Albania with two goals: to assist with the evacuation of expatriates and secure the ground for international organisations.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The main international organisation involved was the Western European Union's multinational Albanian Police element, which worked with the government to restructure the judicial system and simultaneously the Albanian police.
[src:albion/albania-p01] After the fall of the communist system, Albania pursued integration with Euro-Atlantic institutions.
[src:albion/albania-p01] It formally applied for membership of the European Union on 28 April 2009 and joined NATO the same year.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Albania was granted EU candidate status in June 2014, while accession negotiations began with the first intergovernmental conference in July 2022.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Albania opened negotiations on the fundamentals cluster in October 2024 and, by late 2025, had opened all negotiating clusters, a development described by the European Commission as a significant milestone in the accession process.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The 2013 Albanian parliamentary election ended eight years of Democratic Party rule under Sali Berisha.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Socialist Party, led by Edi Rama, won the election as the main force of the Alliance for a European Albania, with the Socialist Movement for Integration as a coalition partner.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Rama's governments promoted judicial reform, public administration changes, urban redevelopment, digitalisation of public services, tourism development and EU accession as central priorities.
[src:albion/albania-p01] A major justice reform package adopted in 2016 created new institutions including the Special Structure against Corruption and Organized Crime (SPAK), which later became central to the prosecution of high-level corruption and organised crime cases.
[src:albion/albania-p01] At the same time, Rama's long tenure became increasingly controversial.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The Socialist Party won the 2017, 2021 and 2025 parliamentary elections, making Rama the first Albanian prime minister to secure four consecutive mandates.
[src:albion/albania-p01] His dominance was accompanied by persistent criticism from opposition parties, civil society and international monitors over corruption, weak checks and balances, state capture, media pressure and the use of state resources in elections.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Freedom House has classified Albania as "Partly Free" and as a "Transitional or Hybrid Regime", while noting that elections are competitive but that politics is highly polarised, organised around dominant personalities, and affected by corruption and bribery.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Freedom House's *Nations in Transit* assessment described Albania's national governance as democratic but dominated by clientelist party politics and individual personalities, and stated that elections were frequently marred by vote-buying, manipulation, fraud and gerrymandering.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Concerns about state capture also became a recurring theme in assessments of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In 2021, Transparency International and the Institute for Democracy and Mediation published *Deconstructing State Capture in Albania*, a report examining grand corruption cases and "tailor-made laws" from 2008 to 2020.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The report argued that state-capture mechanisms in Albania involved clientelist networks, corruption in the judiciary and laws designed to benefit particular private interests.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Electoral integrity remained disputed during Rama's later terms.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The OSCE Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights stated that the 2025 Albanian parliamentary election was competitive and professionally managed, but that it took place in a highly polarised environment and contestants did not enjoy a level playing field.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The final report cited reports of intimidation, misuse of public resources and pressure on public employees, which undermined equal opportunities.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Reuters reported that the 2025 campaign was dominated by Rama's promise to secure EU membership by 2030 and by accusations of widespread corruption, while critics argued that he had concentrated too much power.
[src:albion/albania-p01] After the election, Rama began his fourth term in September 2025 and declared EU membership by 2030 the central goal of his mandate.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The consolidation of Rama's rule coincided with a wave of investigations by SPAK against high-ranking figures from both the governing majority and the opposition.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Deputy prime minister and infrastructure minister Belinda Balluku was later investigated over public-tender allegations, denied wrongdoing, and was dismissed by Rama in February 2026 as the case intensified.
[src:albion/albania-p01] European Union officials praised SPAK's work as central to rule-of-law reform, while also warning that Albania's EU progress depended on judicial independence and credible anti-corruption results.
[src:albion/albania-p01] On 26 November 2019, a 6.4 magnitude earthquake struck Albania, with the epicentre about 16 km (10 mi) southwest of Mamurras.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The tremor was felt in Tirana and in places as far away as Taranto, Italy, and Belgrade, Serbia, while the most affected areas were Durrës and Kodër-Thumanë.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The response included humanitarian aid from the Albanian diaspora and several foreign governments.
[src:albion/albania-p01] On 9 March 2020, the COVID-19 pandemic was confirmed to have spread to Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p01] In 2026, large anti-government demonstrations known as the Flamingo Revolution emerged after proposed luxury coastal developments on Sazan Island and the Zvërnec peninsula, including projects linked to Jared Kushner, became a focus of environmental and anti-corruption protests.
[src:albion/albania-p01] Demonstrators accused Rama's government of lacking transparency, endangering protected ecosystems and failing to tackle corruption or improve public services.
[src:albion/albania-p01] The protests, initially centred on environmental protection, expanded into broader demands for government accountability, early elections and Rama's resignation.
[src:albion/albania-p01] European Parliament figures also warned that the coastal-development plans could affect Albania's EU accession process if they conflicted with environmental obligations and democratic standards.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania lies along the Mediterranean Sea on the Balkan Peninsula in South and Southeast Europe, and has an area of 28,748 km2 (11,100 sq mi).
[src:albion/albania-p02] It is bordered by the Adriatic Sea to the west, Montenegro to the northwest, Kosovo to the northeast, North Macedonia to the east, Greece to the south, and the Ionian Sea to the southwest.
[src:albion/albania-p02] It is between latitudes 42° and 39° N and longitudes 21° and 19° E.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Geographic coordinates include Vërmosh at 42° 35' 34" northern latitude as the northernmost point, Konispol at 39° 40' 0" northern latitude as the southernmost, Sazan at 19° 16' 50" eastern longitude as the westernmost, and Vërnik at 21° 1' 26" eastern longitude as the easternmost.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Mount Korab, rising at 2,764 m (9,068.24 ft) above the Adriatic, is the highest point, while the Mediterranean Sea, at 0 m (0.00 ft), is the lowest.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The country extends 148 km (92 mi) from east to west and around 340 km (211 mi) from north to south.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania has a diverse and varied landscape with mountains and hills that traverse its territory in various directions.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The country is home to extensive mountain ranges, including the Albanian Alps in the north, the Korab Mountains in the east, the Pindus Mountains in the southeast, the Ceraunian Mountains in the southwest, and the Skanderbeg Mountains in the centre.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In the northwest is the Lake of Shkodër, Southern Europe's largest lake.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Towards the southeast emerges the Lake of Ohrid, one of the world's oldest continuously existing lakes.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Farther south, the expanse includes the Large and Small Lake of Prespa, some of the Balkans' highest lakes.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Rivers rise mostly in the east and discharge into the Adriatic and Ionian Seas.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The country's longest river, measured from mouth to source, is the Drin, which starts at the confluence of its two headwaters, the Black and White Drin.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Of particular concern is the Vjosë, one of Europe's last intact large river systems.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In Albania forest cover is around 29.% of the total land area, equivalent to 788,900 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, up from 788,800 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Of the naturally regenerating forest 11% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:albion/albania-p02] For the year 2015, 97% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 3% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The climate of Albania exhibits a distinguished level of variability and diversity due to the differences in latitude, longitude and altitude.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania experiences a Mediterranean and Continental climate, characterised by the presence of four distinct seasons.
[src:albion/albania-p02] According to the Köppen classification, Albania encompasses five primary climatic types, spanning from Mediterranean and subtropical in the western half to oceanic, continental and subarctic in the eastern half of the country.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The coastal regions along the Adriatic and Ionian Seas in Albania are acknowledged as the warmest areas, while the northern and eastern regions encompassing the Albanian Alps and the Korab Mountains are recognised as the coldest areas in the country.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Throughout the year, the average monthly temperatures fluctuate, ranging from −1 °C (30 °F) during the winter months to 21.8 °C (71.2 °F) in the summer months.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Notably, the highest recorded temperature of 43.9 °C (111.0 °F) was observed in Kuçovë on 18 July 1973, while the lowest temperature of −29 °C (−20 °F) was recorded in Shtyllë, Librazhd on 9 January 2017.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania receives most of the precipitation in winter months and less in summer months.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The average precipitation is about 1,485 millimetres (58.5 inches).
[src:albion/albania-p02] The mean annual precipitation ranges between 600 and 3,000 millimetres (24 and 118 inches) depending on geographical location.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The northwestern and southeastern highlands receive the intenser amount of precipitation, whilst the northeastern and southwestern highlands as well as the Western Lowlands the more limited amount.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The Albanian Alps in the far north of the country are considered to be among the most humid regions of Europe, receiving at least 3,100 mm (122.0 in) of rain annually.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Four glaciers within these mountains were discovered at a relatively low altitude of 2,000 metres (6,600 ft), which is extremely rare for such a southerly latitude.
[src:albion/albania-p02] A biodiversity hotspot, Albania possesses an exceptionally rich and contrasting biodiversity on account of its geographical location at the centre of the Mediterranean Sea and the great diversity in its climatic, geological and hydrological conditions.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The estuaries, wetlands and lakes are extraordinarily important for the greater flamingo, pygmy cormorant and the extremely rare and perhaps the most iconic bird of the country, the dalmatian pelican.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Of particular importance are the Mediterranean monk seal, loggerhead sea turtle and green sea turtle that use to nest on the country's coastal waters and shores.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In terms of phytogeography, Albania is part of the Boreal Kingdom and stretches specifically within the Illyrian province of the Circumboreal and Mediterranean Region.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Its territory can be subdivided into four terrestrial ecoregions of the Palearctic realm namely within the Illyrian deciduous forests, Balkan mixed forests, Pindus Mountains mixed forests and Dinaric Mountains mixed forests.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Approximately 3,500 different species of plants can be found in Albania which refers principally to a Mediterranean and Eurasian character.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The country maintains a vibrant tradition of herbal and medicinal practices.
[src:albion/albania-p02] At the minimum 300 plants growing locally are used in the preparation of herbs and medicines.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The trees within the forests are primarily fir, oak, beech and pine.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania has been an active participant in numerous international agreements and conventions aimed at strengthing its commitment to the preservation and sustainable management of biological diversity.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Since 1994, the country is a party to the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) and its associated Cartagena and Nagoya Protocols.
[src:albion/albania-p02] To uphold these commitments, it has developed and implemented a comprehensive National Biodiversity Strategy and Action Plan (NBSAP).
[src:albion/albania-p02] Furthermore, Albania has established a partnership with the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), advancing its conservation efforts on both national and international scales.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Guided by the IUCN, the country has made substantial progress in the foundation of protected areas within its boundaries, encompassing 12 national parks among others Butrint, Karaburun-Sazan, Llogara, Prespa and Vjosa.
[src:albion/albania-p02] As a signatory to the Ramsar Convention, Albania has granted special recognition upon four wetlands, designating them as Wetlands of International Importance, including Buna-Shkodër, Butrint, Karavasta and Prespa.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The country's dedication to protection extends further into the sphere of UNESCO's World Network of Biosphere Reserves, operating within the framework of the Man and the Biosphere Programme, evidenced by its engagement in the Ohrid-Prespa Transboundary Biosphere Reserve.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Furthermore, Albania is host to two natural World Heritage Sites, which encompass the Ohrid region and both the Gashi River and Rrajca as part of Ancient and Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The protected areas of Albania are areas designated and managed by the Albanian government.
[src:albion/albania-p02] There are 12 national parks, 4 ramsar sites, 1 biosphere reserve and 786 other types of conservation reserves in Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Located in the north, the Albanian Alps National Park, comprising the former Theth National Park and Valbonë Valley National Park, is surrounded amidst the towering peaks of the Albanian Alps.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In the east, portions of the rugged Korab, Nemërçka and Shebenik Mountains are conserved within the boundaries of Fir of Hotovë-Dangëlli National Park, Shebenik National Park and Prespa National Park, with the latter encompassing Albania's share of the Great and Small Lakes of Prespa.
[src:albion/albania-p02] To the south, the Ceraunian Mountains define the Albanian Ionian Sea Coast, shaping the landscape of Llogara National Park, which extends into the Karaburun Peninsula, forming the Karaburun-Sazan Marine Park.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Further southward lies Butrint National Park, occupying a peninsula surrounded by the Lake of Butrint and the Channel of Vivari.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In the west, stretching along the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast, the Divjakë-Karavasta National Park boasts the extensive Lagoon of Karavasta, one of the largest lagoon systems in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Notably, Europe's first wild river national park, Vjosa National Park, safeguards the Vjosa River and its primary tributaries, which originates in the Pindus Mountains and flows to the Adriatic Sea.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Dajti Mountain National Park, Lurë-Dejë Mountain National Park and Tomorr Mountain National Park protect the mountainous terrain of the centre of Albania, including the Tomorr and Skanderbeg Mountains.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Environmental issues in Albania notably encompass air and water pollution, climate change impacts, waste management shortcomings, biodiversity loss and imperative for nature conservation.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Climate change is predicted to exert significant impacts on the quality of life in Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania is one of the European countries most at risk and vulnerable to natural disasters.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Natural disasters, such as floods, forest fires, and landslides, are increasing in Albania due to climate change, causing significant damage.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Rising sea levels are anticipated to negatively impact coastal communities and the tourism industry.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In 2023 Albania emitted 7.67 million tonnes of greenhouse gases, equivalent to 2.73 tonnes per person, making it a relatively low emitting country.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania has pledged a 20.9% reduction in GHG emissions by 2030, and net zero by 2050.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The country has a moderate and improving performance in the Environmental Performance Index with an overall ranking of 62 out of 180 countries in 2022.
[src:albion/albania-p02] However, Albania's ranking has decreased since its highest placement at position 15 in the Environmental Performance Index of 2012.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Since declaring independence in 1912, Albania has undergone several major constitutional transformations, including a monarchy, a communist one-party state, and, following the collapse of communism, the establishment of a democratic parliamentary republic.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The current constitutional order was established with the adoption of the Constitution of Albania in 1998, creating a parliamentary constitutional republic based on the separation of powers between the legislature, executive and judiciary.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Executive authority is exercised by the Prime Minister and the Council of Ministers, while the President of Albania serves as head of state with largely ceremonial and constitutional responsibilities.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Legislative authority is vested in the unicameral Parliament of Albania, elected every four years through proportional representation.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Judicial authority is exercised by an independent judiciary headed by the Constitutional Court and the Supreme Court.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Since Edi Rama and the Socialist Party of Albania came to power in 2013, Albania has experienced an unprecedented concentration of executive power, with the Socialist Party winning four consecutive parliamentary elections in 2013, 2017, 2021 and 2025.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Supporters credit Rama's governments with accelerating European Union accession negotiations, implementing the 2016 justice reform, expanding digital public services, improving infrastructure and increasing tourism.
[src:albion/albania-p02] At the same time, Rama's prolonged tenure has generated sustained domestic and international criticism.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Opposition parties, civil society organisations and a number of analysts have argued that Albania has experienced significant democratic backsliding characterised by increasing executive dominance, weakened institutional checks and balances, clientelist governance and extensive political patronage.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Freedom House describes Albania as a "Partly Free" country and notes that politics is dominated by powerful party leaders, while corruption remains a persistent challenge.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Its *Nations in Transit* report characterises Albania's national governance as being dominated by clientelist party politics and states that elections continue to be affected by vote-buying, manipulation, fraud and gerrymandering.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Concerns regarding state capture have also featured prominently in assessments of Albania's political system.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Electoral integrity has remained a contentious issue.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Following the 2025 Albanian parliamentary election, the OSCE Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights concluded that the election was competitive and professionally managed, but found that it was held in a highly polarised environment without a level playing field.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The observation mission reported misuse of public resources, pressure on public employees, intimidation allegations and unequal campaign conditions that undermined equal opportunities among contestants.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The European Commission has generally praised SPAK's work while continuing to stress that corruption remains prevalent in many sectors and that judicial independence must be protected from political pressure.
[src:albion/albania-p02] During Rama's fourth term, anti-government demonstrations intensified.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Beginning in late 2025 and expanding further during the Flamingo Revolution in 2026, protesters accused the government of systemic corruption, lack of transparency, misuse of public resources and favouring politically connected business interests.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The protests, initially triggered by opposition to coastal development projects, evolved into broader demands for democratic reform, government accountability and Rama's resignation.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Human rights protections are guaranteed by the Constitution regardless of ethnicity, language, race or religion.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Nevertheless, international organisations continue to identify concerns regarding judicial independence, corruption, media pluralism and political influence over state institutions, while noting that progress in these areas remains closely linked to Albania's European Union accession process.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Emerging from decades of isolation following the fall of communism, Albania has adopted a foreign policy orientation centred on active cooperation and engagement in international affairs.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The external affairs of Albania underscore the country's dedication to regional stability and integration into major international institutions.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania became a member of the United Nations (UN) in 1955, shortly after emerging from a period of isolation during the communist era.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The country reached a major achievement in its foreign policy by securing NATO membership in 2009.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Since obtaining candidate status in 2014, the country has also embarked on a comprehensive reform agenda to align itself with European Union (EU) accession standards, with the objective of becoming an EU member state.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania and Kosovo maintain a fraternal relationship strengthened by their substantial cultural, ethnical and historical ties.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Both countries foster enduring diplomatic ties, with Albania actively supporting Kosovo's development and international integration efforts.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Its fundamental contribution to Kosovo's path to independence is underscored by its early recognition of Kosovo's sovereignty in 2008.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Furthermore, both governments hold annual joint meetings, displayed by the inaugural meeting in 2014, which serves as an official platform to enhance bilateral cooperation and reinforce their joint commitment to policies that promote the stability and prosperity of the broader Albanian region.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The Albanian Armed Forces consist of Land, Air and Naval Forces and constitute the military and paramilitary forces of the country.
[src:albion/albania-p02] They are led by a commander-in-chief under the supervision of the Ministry of Defence and by the President as the supreme commander during wartime.
[src:albion/albania-p02] However, in times of peace its powers are executed through the Prime Minister and the Defence Minister.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The chief purpose of the armed forces of Albania is the defence of the independence, the sovereignty and the territorial integrity of the country, as well as the participation in humanitarian, combat, non-combat and peace support operations.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Military service is voluntary since 2010 with the age of 19 being the legal minimum age for the duty.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania has committed to increase the participations in multinational operations.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Since the fall of communism, the country has participated in six international missions but only one United Nations mission in Georgia, where it sent three military observers.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Since February 2008, Albania has participated officially in NATO's Operation Active Endeavor in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:albion/albania-p02] It was invited to join NATO on 3 April 2008, and it became a full member on 2 April 2009.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania reduced the number of active troops from 65,000 in 1988 to 14,500 in 2009.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The military now consists mainly of a small fleet of aircraft and sea vessels.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Increasing the military budget was one of the most important conditions for NATO integration.
[src:albion/albania-p02] As of 1996 military spending was an estimated 1.5% of the country's GDP, only to peak in 2009 at 2% and fall again to 1.5%.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Human rights in Albania are formally protected by the Constitution of Albania, which guarantees equality before the law, freedom of expression, freedom of assembly, religious freedom and protection from discrimination.
[src:albion/albania-p02] International assessments generally describe Albania as a competitive but weakened democracy, with persistent problems involving corruption, political pressure on institutions, media freedom, gender-based violence, prison conditions and discrimination against vulnerable groups.
[src:albion/albania-p02] During the long premiership of Edi Rama, whose Socialist Party of Albania has governed since 2013, human-rights concerns have often been linked to broader criticism of democratic backsliding, concentration of executive power, clientelist party politics and weak institutional checks.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Freedom House classifies Albania as "Partly Free" and states that corruption and bribery remain major problems, while its *Nations in Transit* assessment describes national governance as dominated by clientelist party politics and individual personalities.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Opposition parties and critics have characterised Rama's rule as increasingly authoritarian, while the government and its supporters point to judicial reform, European Union accession progress and the work of anti-corruption institutions as evidence of democratic consolidation.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Freedom of expression and media independence remain major concerns.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The United States Department of State's 2024 human-rights report identified serious restrictions on freedom of expression and media freedom, including journalist self-censorship, threats and smear campaigns against journalists reporting on alleged corruption.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Reporters Without Borders has stated that journalists in Albania face political pressure, especially during elections, as well as pressure from media owners and economic insecurity.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In the 2026 World Press Freedom Index, Albania ranked 83rd of 180 countries, with media-rights groups noting continued structural problems affecting editorial independence and journalist safety.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Freedom of assembly is generally recognised, but protest policing has drawn attention during periods of political unrest.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Authorities said the police response followed attacks on officers and damage to property, while protesters and opposition figures accused the government of using force to suppress dissent.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Corruption also has direct implications for human rights and public trust in institutions.
[src:albion/albania-p02] International reports have repeatedly identified corruption in government, law enforcement, the judiciary and local administration as a major problem.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In 2021, Transparency International and the Institute for Democracy and Mediation argued that Albania showed signs of state capture through grand corruption, clientelist networks and tailor-made laws benefiting private interests.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Conditions in prisons and detention facilities have remained a human-rights concern.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Amnesty International reported that people in prisons experienced overcrowding and inadequate healthcare, while the Council of Europe and Albanian authorities have identified prison reform and protection of prisoners' rights as continuing priorities.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Civil-society submissions to the UN Committee against Torture have also raised concerns about overcrowding, poor detention conditions, limited access to legal representation and insufficient investigation of abuse allegations.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Violence against women and girls remains widespread.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Nearly 60% of women in rural areas suffer physical or psychological violence and nearly 8% are victims of sexual violence.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In 2014 the Albanian Helsinki Committee (AHC) reported that the number of female murder victims remained high.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The Commissioner for Protection from Discrimination has raised concerns regarding the family registration law that discriminates against women.
[src:albion/albania-p02] As a result, heads of households, who are overwhelmingly men, have the right to change family residency without their partners' permission.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In 2024, the Council of Europe's GREVIO monitoring body reported progress in Albania's framework against violence against women, but said serious gaps remained, including persistent gender stereotypes, extremely low reporting of sexual violence and limited specialist services.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In 2026, the United Nations in Albania welcomed the adoption of a new law on prevention and protection from violence against women and domestic violence.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Roma, Balkan Egyptian and other minority communities continue to face barriers in education, housing, employment and access to public services.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In 2024, the UN Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination reviewed Albania's implementation of anti-discrimination obligations and discussed the situation of Roma and Egyptian communities, including education, legal aid and hate-speech monitoring.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania has legal protections against discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity, and LGBT organisations hold public events such as Tirana Pride.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In 2015, ILGA-Europe ranked Albania 19th in terms of LGBT rights out of 49 observed European countries.
[src:albion/albania-p02] In the 2022 Rainbow Europe report, lack of progress caused Albania to be ranked 28th among 49 countries.
[src:albion/albania-p02] ILGA-Europe's later country reporting continued to identify discrimination and unsafe school environments for LGBTI people, with a 2024–2025 nationwide survey by Aleanca LGBTI reporting that most respondents viewed schools as unsafe for marginalised groups, including LGBTI students.
[src:albion/albania-p02] are the first-level administrative units in Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Albania is defined within a territorial area of 28,748 km2 (11,100 sq mi) in the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:albion/albania-p02] It is informally divided into three regions, the Northern, Central and Southern Regions.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Since its Declaration of Independence in 1912, Albania has reformed its internal organisation 21 times.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Presently, the primary administrative units are the twelve constituent counties (*qarqe/qarqet*), which hold equal status under the law.
[src:albion/albania-p02] Counties had previously been used in the 1950s and were recreated on 31 July 2000 to unify the 36 districts (*rrathë/rrathët*) of that time.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The largest county in Albania by population is Tirana County with over 800,000 people.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The smallest county, by population, is Gjirokastër County with over 70,000 people.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The largest county, by area, is Korçë County encompassing 3,711 square kilometres (1,433 sq mi) of the southeast of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The smallest county, by area, is Durrës County with an area of 766 square kilometres (296 sq mi) in the west of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p02] The counties are made up of 61 second-level divisions known as municipalities (*bashki/bashkia*).
[src:albion/albania-p02] The municipalities are the first level of local governance, responsible for local needs and law enforcement.
[src:albion/albania-p02] They unified and simplified the previous system of urban and rural municipalities or communes (*komuna/komunat*) in 2015.
[src:albion/albania-p02] For smaller issues of local government, the municipalities are organised into 373 administrative units (*njësia*/*njësitë administrative*).
[src:albion/albania-p02] There are also 2980 villages (*fshatra/fshatrat*), neighborhoods or wards (*lagje/lagjet*), and localities (*lokalitete/lokalitetet*) previously used as administrative units.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Transitioning from a socialist planned to a capitalist mixed economy, Albania is classified as a developing open market with an upper-middle income status.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Albanian economy is characterised by a substantial service sector, comprising 48.6% of GDP, with key contributions from wholesale and retail trade, tourism, real estate, and logistics.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Following this, the industrial sector accounts for 20.2%, particularly influenced by construction, while the agricultural sector, including forestry, and fisheries, represents 18.5%, and the manufacturing sector contributes a modest 6.3% to the economy.
[src:albion/albania-p03] As of 2025, Albania's nominal gross domestic product (GDP) is reported at $26.911 billion with a GDP per capita of $9,474.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The projected annual percentage change in economic growth for 2025 is 3.8%, with a forecasted moderation to 3.5% by 2029.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania has developed a comprehensive framework for international trade through several pivotal agreements with various regions.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Stabilisation and Association Agreement (SAA) with the European Union (EU), signed in 2006, is one of the most significant.
[src:albion/albania-p03] This agreement provides critical trade benefits and serves as a foundation for the Albanian integration into the EU.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In 2009, Albania signed a free trade agreement (FTA) with the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), which further expands trade opportunities and market access.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The country is also a signatory to the Central European Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA) and Organization of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation (BSEC), promoting regional trade and collaboration with neighboring countries.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Furthermore, the country has enhanced its bilateral trade relations through a FTA with Turkey, the United Kingdom and a bilateral investment treaty with the United States.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The 2023 Economic Freedom of the World report placed Albania in the 31st position, noting a considerable degree of economic independence and the effective adoption of market-oriented policies.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The 2024 Bertelsmann Transformation Index ranked Albania 20th and acknowledged substantial progress in political and economic transformation.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Also in 2024, the country was positioned 23rd in the Global Gender Gap Index, excelling in the Economic Participation and Opportunity category with a global ranking of 16th, showcasing significant advancements in women's economic participation.
[src:albion/albania-p03] However, the Albanian economy, despite demonstrating considerable resilience, encounters substantial vulnerabilities that hinder its development.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Principal challenges include widespread corruption, distorted competition, and frequent modifications to fiscal legislation.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Furthermore, inadequate contract enforcement, a large informal sector, and persistent labor shortages further complicate the national economic progress.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Economic landscape of Albania is characterised by regional disparities, particularly apparent in the concentration of economic activities in the triangular region formed by Tirana, Durrës and Laç.
[src:albion/albania-p03] This metropolitan area, referred to as Durana, functions as the principal economic center of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In the year 2021, Tirana County accounted for a significant 44% of the national GDP, with the counties of Fier and Durrës also playing integral roles in the economy, contributing 11% and 10% to the GDP, respectively.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Other substantial economic centers, such as Elbasan and the coastal cities of Sarandë and Vlorë, highlight the uneven distribution of economic development across the country.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Cultural regions, including Berat and Korçë, despite their geographical distance from the primary economic hubs, have derived considerable benefits from the expansion of the tourism sector.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Concerns over illicit finance, money laundering and organised-crime influence have become increasingly prominent in assessments of Albania's economy.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The United States Department of State has identified Albania as vulnerable to money laundering, with criminal proceeds laundered through real estate purchases, construction projects, virtual assets and business development.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Its 2025 Investment Climate Statement also described Albania's economic development as vulnerable because of widespread corruption, organised crime, distorted competition, labour shortages, low productivity and a large informal sector.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Global Initiative Against Transnational Organized Crime's 2025 Global Organized Crime Index described Albania as a prominent destination for money laundering, stating that criminal organisations exploit the real estate, tourism and construction sectors to legitimise illicit profits.
[src:albion/albania-p03] It also reported that the construction sector is heavily infiltrated by illicit funds, distorting the market, and that corruption within political and law-enforcement institutions continues to facilitate organised crime.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The government has generally rejected accusations of political protection for organised crime and has pointed to justice reform, anti-money-laundering measures and investigations by the Special Structure against Corruption and Organized Crime as evidence of progress.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Further, the country is a worldwide significant producer of salvia, rosemary and yellow gentian.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The country's proximity to the Ionian Sea and the Adriatic Sea give the underdeveloped fishing industry great potential.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The World Bank and European Community economists report that, Albania's fishing industry has good potential to generate export earnings because prices in the nearby Greek and Italian markets are many times higher than those in the Albanian market.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The fish available off the coasts of the country are carp, trout, sea bream, mussels and crustaceans.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania has one of Europe's longest histories of viticulture.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Today's region was one of the few places where vine was naturally grown during the ice age.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The oldest found seeds in the region are 4,000 to 6,000 years old.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In 2009, the nation produced an estimated 17,500 tonnes of wine.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania's secondary sector has undergone many changes and diversification since the communist regime collapsed.
[src:albion/albania-p03] It is very diversified, from electronics, manufacturing, textiles, to food, cement, mining, and energy.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Antea Cement plant in Fushë-Krujë is considered one of the nation's largest industrial greenfield investments.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albanian oil and gas is one of the most promising, albeit strictly regulated, sectors of its economy.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania has the second-largest oil deposits in the Balkan peninsula after Romania, and the largest oil reserves in Europe.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Albpetrol company is owned by the Albanian state and monitors the state petroleum agreements in the country.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The textile industry has seen an extensive expansion by approaching companies from the European Union (EU) in Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] According to the Instituti i Statistikës (INSTAT), as of 2016, textile production had an annual growth of 5.3% and an annual turnover of around 1.5 billion euros.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania is a significant minerals producer and ranks among the world's leading chromium producers and exporters.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The nation is also a notable producer of copper, nickel, and coal.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Batra mine, Bulqizë mine, and Thekna mine are among the most recognised Albanian mines still in operation.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The tertiary sector represents the fastest growing sector of the country's economy.
[src:albion/albania-p03] 36% of the population work in the service sector which contributes to 65% of the country's GDP.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Ever since the end of the 20th century, the banking industry is a major component of the tertiary sector and remains in good conditions overall due to privatisation and the commendable monetary policy.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Previously one of the most isolated and controlled countries in the world, telecommunication industry represents nowadays another major contributor to the sector.
[src:albion/albania-p03] It developed largely through privatisation and subsequent investment by both domestic and foreign investors.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Eagle, Vodafone and Telekom Albania are the leading telecommunications service providers in the country.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Tourism is recognised as an industry of national importance and has been steadily increasing since the beginnings of the 21st century.
[src:albion/albania-p03] It directly accounted for 8.4% of GDP in 2016 though including indirect contributions pushes the proportion to 26%.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In the same year, the country received approximately 4.74 million visitors mostly from across Europe and the United States as well.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The increase of foreign visitors has been dramatic.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania had only 500,000 visitors in 2005, and an estimated 4.2 million in 2012, an increase of 740 percent.
[src:albion/albania-p03] According to the United Nations World Tourism Organization (UN Tourism), Albania welcomed approximately 11.7 million tourists in 2024, marking a significant increase from previous years.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The bulk of the tourist industry is concentrated along the Adriatic and Ionian Sea in the west of the country.
[src:albion/albania-p03] But the Albanian Riviera in the southwest has the most scenic and pristine beaches; its coastline has a considerable length of 446 kilometres (277 miles).
[src:albion/albania-p03] The coast has a distinctive character, rich in varieties of virgin beaches, capes, coves, covered bays, lagoons, small gravel beaches, sea caves, and many landforms.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Some parts of this seaside are very clean ecologically, including unexplored areas, which are very rare within the Mediterranean.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Other attractions include the mountainous areas such as the Albanian Alps, Ceraunian Mountains and Korab Mountains but also the historical cities of Berat, Durrës, Gjirokastër, Sarandë, Shkodër and Korçë.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The international airport of Tirana is the premier air gateway to the country, and is also the principal hub for Albania's national flag carrier airline, Air Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The airport carried more than 3.3 million passengers in 2019 with connections to many destinations in other countries around Europe, Africa and Asia.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The country plans to progressively increase the number of airports especially in the south with possible locations in Sarandë, Gjirokastër and Vlorë.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The highways and motorways in Albania are properly maintained and often still under construction and renovation.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Autostrada 1 (A1) is an integral transportation corridor and the country's longest motorway.
[src:albion/albania-p03] It is planned to link Durrës on the Adriatic Sea across Pristina in Kosovo with the Pan-European Corridor X in Serbia.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Autostrada 2 (A2) is part of the Adriatic–Ionian Corridor as well as the Pan-European Corridor VIII and connects Fier with Vlorë.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Autostrada 3 (A3) is under construction and after its completion will connect Tirana and Elbasan with the Pan-European Corridor VIII.
[src:albion/albania-p03] When all three corridors are completed, Albania will have an estimated 759 kilometres (472 mi) of highway, linking it with all neighboring countries.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Durrës is the busiest and largest seaport in the country, followed by Vlorë, Shëngjin and Sarandë.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The rail network is administered by the national railway company Hekurudha Shqiptare.
[src:albion/albania-p03] A new railway line from Tirana and its airport to Durrës is planned.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The location of this railway, connecting Albania's most populated urban areas, makes it an important economic development project.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Due to its location and natural resources, Albania has a wide variety of energy resources, ranging from gas, oil, and coal to wind, solar, water, and other renewable sources.
[src:albion/albania-p03] According to the World Economic Forum's 2023 Energy Transition Index (ETI), the country ranked 21st globally, highlighting the progress in its energy transition agenda.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Currently, Albania's electricity generation sector depends on hydroelectricity, ranking fifth in the world in percentage terms.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Increasing risks of river floods and droughts due to climate change is expected to put electricity generation at risk.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Drin, in the north, hosts four hydroelectric power stations, including Fierza, Koman, Skavica and Vau i Dejës.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Two other power stations, such as the Banjë and Moglicë, are along the Devoll in the south.
[src:albion/albania-p03] It has the 10th-largest oil reserves in Europe and the 58th in the world.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The country's main petroleum deposits are located around the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast and Myzeqe Plain within the Western Lowlands, where the country's largest reserve is located.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Patos-Marinza, also located within the area, is the largest onshore oil field in Europe.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Trans Adriatic Pipeline (TAP), part of the planned Southern Gas Corridor, runs for 215 kilometres (134 miles) across Albania's territory before entering the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast approximately 17 kilometres (11 miles) northwest of Fier.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania's water resources are particularly abundant in all the regions of the country and comprise lakes, rivers, springs, and groundwater aquifers.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The country's available average quantity of fresh water is estimated at 129.7 cubic metres (4,580 cubic feet) per inhabitant per year, one of the highest rates in Europe.
[src:albion/albania-p03] According to data presented by the Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation (JMP) in 2015, about 93% of the country's total population had access to improved sanitation.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The freedom of press and freedom of speech, and the right to free expression are guaranteed by the Constitution of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In practice, however, media freedom has been weakened by political pressure, concentrated ownership, opaque financing, intimidation of journalists and the overlap between media, business and political interests.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania ranked 84th in the World Press Freedom Index of 2020 compiled by Reporters Without Borders.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders has continued to describe the Albanian media environment as fragile, stating that press freedom and media independence are threatened by conflicts of interest between business and politics, a flawed legal framework and partisan regulation.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In 2026, Albania ranked 83rd of 180 countries in the World Press Freedom Index.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Radio Televizioni Shqiptar (RTSH) is the public broadcaster of Albania, operating television and radio stations throughout the country.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The main private broadcasters include Top Channel, TV Klan, Vizion Plus, A2 CNN, Syri TV and Ora News.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albanian television content is also distributed in Kosovo and other Albanian-speaking territories.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders states that the most influential private-sector media are owned by a small number of companies with links to the political world and to highly regulated sectors such as construction.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Media Freedom Rapid Response reported that the top four owners in the Albanian television market reach between 48.93% and 58.60% of audiences, and that the boundaries between media, politics and economics remain blurred.
[src:albion/albania-p03] According to these assessments, media owners often use their outlets to protect business interests or influence governments and political parties, while state advertising and public funds are distributed in opaque ways that can create political dependence.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The media environment has become a central part of criticism of Prime Minister Edi Rama's long rule.
[src:albion/albania-p03] International media-freedom organisations and Albanian journalists have accused the government of using communication centralisation, selective access, public-relations material and attacks on critical reporters to dominate the information space.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders has stated that journalists face political pressure, especially during elections, and that politicians limit editorial independence by politicising regulators and the public broadcaster.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Media Freedom Rapid Response cited BIRN Albania editor Gjergj Erebara as saying that large parts of the Albanian media landscape operate under government propaganda and disinformation pressure.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Journalists who investigate corruption, organised crime or politically connected business interests face particular risks.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Reporters Without Borders states that journalists investigating crime and corruption are frequent targets of threats and that self-censorship is widespread.
[src:albion/albania-p03] It also reports that critical journalists are subjected to discrediting attacks by both government and opposition politicians, while organised crime remains a major threat to journalists' safety.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In March 2023, the headquarters of Top Channel was attacked with automatic weapons, killing a security guard.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The public broadcaster has also been part of the debate over media capture and political pressure.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In 2026, international media-freedom organisations warned that democratic reform of RTSH should not be carried out through funding cuts, suspension or closure, arguing that such measures would violate European standards for public service media.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albanian cinema has its roots in the 20th century and developed after the country's declaration of independence.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The first movie theater exclusively devoted to showing motion pictures was built in 1912 in Shkodër.
[src:albion/albania-p03] During the People's Republic of Albania, Albanian cinema developed rapidly with the inauguration of the Kinostudio Shqipëria e Re in Tirana.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In 1953, the Albanian-Soviet epic film *The Great Warrior Skanderbeg* was released, chronicling the life and fight of the medieval Albanian hero Skanderbeg.
[src:albion/albania-p03] It went on to win an international prize at the 1954 Cannes Film Festival.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In 2003, the Tirana International Film Festival was established, the largest film festival in the country.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Durrës Amphitheatre hosts the Durrës International Film Festival, the country's second largest film festival.
[src:albion/albania-p03] After the fall of communism in 1991, human resources in sciences and technology in Albania have drastically decreased.
[src:albion/albania-p03] As of various reports, during 1991 to 2005 approximately 50% of the professors and scientists of the universities and science institutions in the country have left Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania was ranked 67th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Telecommunication represents one of the fastest growing and dynamic sectors in Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Vodafone Albania, Telekom Albania and Albtelecom are the three large providers of mobile and internet in Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] As of the Electronic and Postal Communications Authority (AKEP) in 2018, the country had approximately 2.7 million active mobile users with almost 1.8 million active broadband subscribers.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Vodafone Albania alone served more than 931,000 mobile users, Telekom Albania had about 605,000 users and Albtelecom had more than 272,000 users.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In January 2023, Albania launched its first two satellites, *Albania 1* and *Albania 2*, into orbit, in what was regarded as a milestone effort in monitoring the country's territory and identifying illegal activities.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albanian-American engineer Mira Murati, the Chief Technology Officer of research organisation OpenAI, played a substantial role in the development and launch of artificial intelligence services such as ChatGPT, Codex and DALL-E.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In December 2023, Prime Minister Edi Rama announced plans for collaboration between the Albanian government and ChatGPT, facilitated by discussions with Murati.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Rama emphasised the intention to streamline the alignment of Albanian laws with the regulations of the European Union, aiming to reduce costs associated with translation and legal services.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The demographic statistics of Albania, as revealed by the 2023 census conducted by the Instituti i Statistikave (INSTAT), indicated a population of 2,402,113, with a notable decline from the 2,821,977 recorded in the 2011 census.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The decrease in inhabitants began after the disintegration of the communist regime in Albania and is associated with significant shifts within the political, economic, and social structure of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] A principal factor in this transition incorporates a decline in fertility rates coupled with an increase in emigration, both contributing to persistent demographic changes and challenges.
[src:albion/albania-p03] It is forecast that the population will continue shrinking for the next decade at least, depending on the actual rates and the level of migration.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Currently, the population density of Albania is measured at 83.6 inhabitants per square kilometer with a varied distribution of inhabitants across different regions.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The counties of Tirana and Durrës showcase substantial concentrations of people, accounting for about 41% of the overall demographic of Albania, with 32% residing in Tirana and 9% in Durrës.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Conversely, more peripheral and rural counties such as Gjirokastër and Kukës present significantly lower population densities, with each aiding 3% to the overall population.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Historically, the Albanian people have established several communities in many regions throughout Southern Europe.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Albanian diaspora has been formed since the late Middle Ages, when they emigrated to escape either various socio-political difficulties or the Ottoman conquest of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Following the fall of communism, large numbers of Albanians have migrated to countries such as Australia, Canada, Switzerland, the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albanian minorities are present in the neighbouring territories such as the west of North Macedonia, the southeast of Montenegro, Kosovo in its entirety and parts of southern Serbia.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Altogether, the number of ethnic Albanians living abroad is estimated to be higher than the total population inside Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] As much as a third of those born in the country's borders now live outside of it, making Albania one of the countries with the highest rate of outmigration relative to its population in the world.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In 2022 the birth rate was 20% lower than in 2021, largely due to emigration of people of childbearing age.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Subsequent to the collapse of communism in 1991, Albania has undergone a remarkable transformation in its urban landscape, emerging as one of the fastest urbanising countries in Europe.
[src:albion/albania-p03] At the forefront of this transformation is the Tirana–Durrës agglomeration, a densely populated urban corridor situated along the western coast of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] This corridor has become the primary locus of population growth and settlement development, attracting a significant influx of internal migrants from the country's peripheral areas.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Despite an overall decline of the country's total population, the proportion of the urban demographic has consistently progressed from 47% in 2001 to 65% in 2023.
[src:albion/albania-p03] This sustained increase, coupled with the concentration in the Tirana-Durrës region, has led to a spread of regional imbalances, with the peripheral areas, particularly Dibër and Kukës, experiencing severe depopulation.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The official language of the country is Albanian which is spoken by the vast majority of the country's population.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Its standard spoken and written form is revised and merged from the two main dialects, Gheg and Tosk, though it is notably based more on the Tosk dialect.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Shkumbin river is the rough dividing line between the two dialects.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Among minority languages, Greek is the second most-spoken language in the country, with 0.5 to 3% of the population speaking it as first language, mainly in the country's south where its speakers are concentrated.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Other languages spoken by ethnic minorities in Albania include Aromanian, Serbo-Croatian, Macedonian, Bulgarian, Gorani, and Roma.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Macedonian is official in the Pustec Municipality in East Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In the 2023 population census, 91.07% reported Albanian as the language spoken at home.
[src:albion/albania-p03] 1.54% declared to speak at home another language, 0.57% multiple languages, 1.21% gave no answer and 5.59% were unavailable.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Among young people aged 25 or less, English, German and Turkish have seen rising interest after 2000.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Italian and French have had a stable interest, while Greek has lost much of its previous interest.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The trends are linked with cultural and economic factors.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In the mid-2010s, an increasing number of Albanians showed interest in learning the German language, which has been explained as part of "a Western Balkan trend of preparing to integrate into the German labor market".
[src:albion/albania-p03] Some of them have gone to Germany for studies or work.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania and Germany have agreements for cooperating in helping young people of the two countries know both cultures better.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Due to a sharp rise in economic relations with Turkey, interest in learning Turkish, in particular among young people, was also growing on a yearly basis in the 2010s.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Designated national and cultural minorities in Albania include Aromanian, Greek, Macedonian, Montenegrin, Serb, Roma, Egyptian, Bosnian and Bulgarian peoples, as well as Gorani and Jews as other minority groups.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania is a secular and religiously diverse country with no official religion.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Freedom of religion, belief and conscience are guaranteed under the country's constitution.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania is nevertheless ranked among the least religious countries in the world.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Religion constitute an important role in the lives of only 39% of the country's population.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In another report, 56% considered themselves religious, 30% considered themselves non-religious, while 9% defined themselves as convinced atheists.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The Muslim Albanians are spread throughout the country.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Orthodox and Bektashis are mostly found in the south, whereas Catholics mainly live in the north.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In 2008, there were 694 Catholic churches and 425 Orthodox churches, 568 mosques and 70 bektashi takyas in the country.
[src:albion/albania-p03] During modern times, the Albanian republican, monarchic and later communist regimes followed a systematic policy of separating religion from official functions and cultural life.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The country has never had an official religion either as a republic or as a kingdom.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In the 20th century, the clergy of all faiths was weakened under the monarchy and ultimately eradicated during the 1950s and 1960s, under the state policy of obliterating all organised religion from the territories of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The communist regime persecuted and suppressed religious observance and institutions and entirely banned religion.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The country was then officially declared to be the world's first atheist state.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Religious freedom has returned, however, since the end of communism.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Islam survived communist era persecution and reemerged in the modern era as a practised religion in Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Some smaller Christian sects in Albania include Evangelicals and several Protestant communities including Seventh-day Adventist Church, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints and Jehovah's Witnesses.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The first recorded Protestant of Albania was Said Toptani, who travelled around Europe and returned to Tirana in 1853, where he preached Protestantism.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The first evangelical Protestants appeared in the 19th century and the Evangelical Alliance was founded in 1892.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Nowadays, it has 160 member congregations from different Protestant denominations.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Following mass emigration to Israel after the fall of communism, there are only 200 Albanian Jews left in the country.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In Albania, education is secular, free, compulsory, and based on three levels.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The academic year is apportioned into two semesters, beginning in September or October and ending in June or July.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albanian is the primary language of instruction in the country's academic institutions.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The study of a first foreign language is mandatory and taught most often at elementary and bilingual schools.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Languages taught in schools are English, Italian, French and German.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Albania has a school life expectancy of 16 years and a literacy rate of 98.7%, with 99.2% for men and 98.3% for women.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Compulsory primary education is divided into two levels, elementary and secondary school, from grade one to five and six to nine, respectively.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Pupils are required to attend school from the age six until they turn 16.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Upon successful completion of primary education, all pupils are entitled to attend high schools, specialising in any field, including arts, sports, languages, sciences, and technology.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Tertiary education is optional and has undergone a thorough reformation and restructuring in compliance with the principles of the Bologna Process.
[src:albion/albania-p03] There are a significant number of private and public institutions of higher education in Albania's major cities.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Tertiary education is organised into three successive levels, the bachelor, master, and doctorate.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The constitution of Albania guarantees its citizens equal, free, and universal health care.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The health care system is organised into primary, secondary, and tertiary healthcare, and is in a process of modernisation and development.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The life expectancy at birth in Albania is 77.8 years, ranking 37th in the world and surpassing several developed countries.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The average healthy life expectancy is 68.8 years, ranking 37th in the world.
[src:albion/albania-p03] The country's infant mortality rate was estimated at 12 per 1,000 live births in 2015.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In 2000, the country had the world's 55th-best healthcare performance, as defined by the World Health Organisation (WHO).
[src:albion/albania-p03] Cardiovascular disease is the principal cause of death in Albania, accounting for 52% of deaths.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Accidents, injuries, malignant and respiratory diseases are other primary causes of death.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Neuropsychiatric disease has also increased due to recent demographic, social, and economic changes in the country.
[src:albion/albania-p03] In 2009, Albania had a fruit and vegetable supply of 886 grams per capita per day, the fifth-highest supply in Europe.
[src:albion/albania-p03] Compared to other developed and developing countries, Albania has a relatively low rate of obesity, probably thanks to the Mediterranean diet.
[src:albion/albania-p03] According to 2016 WHO data, 21.7% of adults in the country are clinically overweight, with a Body mass index (BMI) score of 25 or more.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The red and black national colours are displayed on the flag of Albania that is adorned with a double-headed eagle as the foremost recognised national symbol of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p04] With the black eagle portraying bravery and strength, the red field symbolises the fortitude and sacrifices of the Albanian people.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The eagle is linked with the legacy of the national hero Gjergj Kastrioti, renowned as Skanderbeg, who led a prosperous resistance movement against Ottoman rule.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Rooted in the Middle Ages, it emerged as a heraldic symbol in the Principality of Arbër and among notable Albanian dynasties such as the Dukagjini, Kastrioti, Muzaka and Thopia clans.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Amid the Albanian Renaissance, marking the resurgence of Albanian national identity and aspirations for independence, the Albanian eagle regained its prominence.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Its importance reached its culmination with Albania's declaration of independence in 1912, when Ismail Qemali raised it as the national flag in Vlorë.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The coat of arms of Albania is an adaptation of the flag of Albania and the seal of Skanderbeg.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The coat comprises the black double-headed eagle positioned at the centre of a red field.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Above the eagle, it carries the helmet of Skanderbeg that is crowned with the head of a golden horned goat.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Ti Shqipëri, më jep nder, më jep emrin Shqipëtar, which translates to "You Albania, give me honour, give me the name Albanian", is the national motto of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p04] It finds its foundation in the legacy of national poet Naim Frashëri, who held a renowned role during the Albanian Renaissance.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The national anthem of Albania, "Himni i Flamurit", was composed by Asdreni and adopted as such following Albania's independence in 1912.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albanian traditional clothing, with its contrasting variations for the northern Gheg and southern Tosk Albanians, is a testament to Albania's history, cultural diversity and ethnic identity.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Gheg men wear a light-colored shirt paired with wide loose-fitting trousers referred to as the Tirq.
[src:albion/albania-p04] These trousers are securely fastened by a wide woven belt, the Brez.
[src:albion/albania-p04] An integral component of their costume is the Xhamadan, a woolen red velvet vest adorned with folkloric motifs and gold patterns.
[src:albion/albania-p04] They also wear a distinctive dome-shaped hat known as the Qeleshe, crafted from wool, with its origins tracing back to the Illyrians.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Conversely, Tosk men opt for the Fustanella, a knee-length garment designated as the national costume, typically white with pleats, accompanied by a white shirt.
[src:albion/albania-p04] They also wear a beige or dark blue Xhamadan reminiscent of the Gheg attire.
[src:albion/albania-p04] To complete their attire, men wear knee-high socks referred to as Çorape and leather shoes known as Opinga.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The attire of Gheg and Tosk women is renowned for its rich palette of colors and intricate filigree detailing, displayed across various components including ear ornaments, finger rings, necklaces, belt buckles and buttons.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Key components include a long, light-toned shirt paired with an apron, often accompanied by a woolen or felt mantle referred to as the Xhoka.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Additional upper garments, such as the Dollama or Mintan, may be layered, along with a headscarf known as Kapica or Shall.
[src:albion/albania-p04] A distinctive variation incorporates a pair of aprons, including the Pështjellak at the rear and the Paranik at the front.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Integral to the traditional attire of Gheg women is the ancient Xhubleta.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Dedicated efforts have been undertaken to preserve and promote the dress, acknowledging its significance as an emblem of Albanian heritage.
[src:albion/albania-p04] As a testament to its importance, the Xhubleta has been inscribed on the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage List.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The distinctive bell-shaped garment is fashioned in black and enriched with embroidered ethnic Albanian motifs, showcasing the remarkable craftsmanship of northern Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Its crafting process involves multiple intricate stages, encompassing the preparation of shajak fabric and the precise cutting techniques.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The artistic history of Albania has been particularly influenced by a multitude of ancient and medieval people, traditions and religions.
[src:albion/albania-p04] It covers a broad spectrum with mediums and disciplines that include painting, pottery, sculpture, ceramics and architecture all of them exemplifying a great variety in style and shape, in different regions and period.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The rise of the Byzantine and Ottoman Empire in the Middle Ages was accompanied by a corresponding growth in Christian and Islamic art in the lands of Albania which are apparent in examples of architecture and mosaics throughout the country.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Centuries later, the Albanian Renaissance proved crucial to the emancipation of the modern Albanian culture and saw unprecedented developments in all fields of literature and art whereas artists sought to return to the ideals of Impressionism and Romanticism.
[src:albion/albania-p04] However, Onufri, Kolë Idromeno, David Selenica, Kostandin Shpataraku and the Zografi Brothers are the most eminent representatives of Albanian art.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The architecture of Albania reflects the legacy of various civilisations tracing back to the classical antiquity.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Major cities in Albania have evolved from within the castle to include dwellings, religious and commercial structures, with constant redesigning of town squares and evolution of building techniques.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Nowadays, the cities and towns reflect a whole spectrum of various architectural styles.
[src:albion/albania-p04] In the 20th century, many historical as well as sacred buildings bearing the ancient influence were demolished during the communist era.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Ancient architecture is found throughout Albania and most visible in Byllis, Amantia, Phoenice, Apollonia, Butrint, Antigonia, Shkodër and Durrës.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Considering the long period of rule of the Byzantine Empire, they introduced castles, citadels, churches and monasteries with spectacular wealth of visible murals and frescos.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Perhaps the best known examples can be found in the southern Albanian cities and surroundings of Korçë, Berat, Voskopojë and Gjirokastër.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Involving the introduction of Ottoman architecture there was a development of mosques and other Islamic buildings, particularly seen in Berat and Gjirokastër.
[src:albion/albania-p04] A productive period of Historicism, Art Nouveau and Neoclassicism merged into the 19th century, best exemplified in Korçë.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The 20th century brought new architectural styles such as the modern Italian style, which is present in Tirana such as the Skanderbeg Square and Ministries.
[src:albion/albania-p04] It is also present in Shkodër, Vlorë, Sarandë and Durrës.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Moreover, other towns received their present-day Albania-unique appearance through various cultural or economic influences.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Socialist classicism arrived during the communist era in Albania after the Second World War.
[src:albion/albania-p04] At this period many socialist-styled complexes, wide roads and factories were constructed, while town squares were redesigned and numerous of historic and important buildings demolished.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Notable examples of that style include the Mother Teresa Square, Pyramid of Tirana, Palace of Congresses and so on.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Three Albanian archaeological sites are included in the list of UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:albion/albania-p04] These include the ancient remains of Butrint, the medieval Historic Centres of Berat and Gjirokastër, and Natural and Cultural Heritage of the Ohrid region site shared with North Macedonia since 2019.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Furthermore, the royal Illyrian tombs, the remains of Apollonia, the ancient Amphitheatre of Durrës and the Fortress of Bashtovë has been included on the tentative list of Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albanian folk music is a prominent part of the national identity, and continues to play a major part in overall Albanian music.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Folk music can be divided into two stylistic groups, mainly the northern Gheg varieties, and southern Lab and Tosk varieties.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Northern and southern traditions are contrasted by a rugged tone from the north, and the more relaxed southern form of music.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Many songs concern events from Albanian history and culture, including traditional themes of honour, hospitality, treachery, and revenge.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The first compilation of Albanian folk music was made by two Himariot musicians, Neço Muka and Koço Çakali, in Paris, during their work with Albanian soprano Tefta Tashko-Koço.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Several gramophone compilations were recorded at the time by the three artists, which eventually led to the recognition of Albanian iso-polyphony as a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Festivali i Këngës is a traditional Albanian song contest organised by the national broadcaster Radio Televizioni Shqiptar (RTSH).
[src:albion/albania-p04] The festival is celebrated annually since its inauguration in 1962 and has launched the careers of some of Albania's most successful singers including Vaçe Zela and Parashqevi Simaku.
[src:albion/albania-p04] It is significantly a music competition among Albanian performers presenting unreleased songs in premiere, composed by Albanian authors and voted by juries or by public.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Contemporary artists Rita Ora, Bebe Rexha, Era Istrefi, Dua Lipa, Ava Max, Bleona, Elvana Gjata, Ermonela Jaho, and Inva Mula have achieved international recognition for their music, while soprano Ermonela Jaho has been described by some as the "world's most acclaimed soprano".
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albanian opera singer Saimir Pirgu was nominated for the 2017 Grammy Award.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The cultural renaissance was first of all expressed through the development of the Albanian language in the area of church texts and publications.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The Protestant reforms invigorated hopes for the development of the local language and literary tradition, when cleric Gjon Buzuku translated the Catholic liturgy into Albanian, trying to do for Albanian what Martin Luther had done for German.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Meshari (*The Missal*) written by Gjon Buzuku was published in 1555 and is considered one of the first literary work of written Albanian during the Middle Ages.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The refined level of the language and the stabilised orthography must be the result of an earlier tradition of written Albanian, a tradition that is not well understood.
[src:albion/albania-p04] However, there is some fragmented evidence, pre-dating Buzuku, which indicates that Albanian was written from at least the 14th century.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albanian writings from these centuries must not have been religious texts only, but historical chronicles too.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The *History of Skanderbeg* is still the foundation of Skanderbeg studies and is considered an Albanian cultural treasure, vital to the formation of Albanian national self-consciousness.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The most famous Albanian writer in the 20th and 21st century is probably Ismail Kadare.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Throughout the centuries, Albanian cuisine has been widely influenced by Albanian culture, geography and history, and as such, different parts of the country enjoy specific regional cuisines.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Cooking traditions especially vary between the north and the south, owing to differing topography and climate that essentially contribute to the excellent growth conditions for a wide array of herbs, fruits, and vegetables.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albanians produce and use many varieties of fruits such as lemons, oranges, figs, and most notably, olives, which are perhaps the most important element of Albanian cooking.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Spices and other herbs such as basil, lavender, mint, oregano, rosemary, and thyme are widely used, as are vegetables such as garlic, onions, peppers, potatoes, tomatoes, as well as legumes of all types.
[src:albion/albania-p04] With a coastline along the Adriatic and Ionian in the Mediterranean Sea, fish, crustaceans, and seafood are a popular and an integral part of the Albanian diet.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Otherwise, lamb is the traditional meat for different holidays and religious festivals for both Christians and Muslims, although poultry, beef, and pork are also in plentiful supply.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Tavë kosi ("soured milk casserole") is the national dish of Albania, consisting of lamb and rice baked under a thick, tart veil of yoghurt.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Fërgesë is another national dish, made up of peppers, tomatoes, and cottage cheese.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Pite is also popular, a baked pastry with a filling of a mixture of spinach and gjizë (curd) or mish (ground meat).
[src:albion/albania-p04] Petulla, a traditional fried dough, is also a popular speciality, and is served with powdered sugar or feta cheese and different sorts of fruit jams.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Flia consists of multiple crêpe-like layers brushed with cream and served with sour cream.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Krofne, similar to Berliner doughnuts, are filled with jam, or chocolate and often eaten during winter.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Coffee is an integral part of the Albanian lifestyle.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The country has more coffee houses per capita than any other country in the world.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Tea is also enjoyed both at home or outside at cafés, bars, or restaurants. Çaj Mali (Sideritis tea) is enormously beloved, and a part of the daily routine for most Albanians.
[src:albion/albania-p04] It is cultivated across Southern Albania and noted for its medicinal properties.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albanian wine is also common throughout the country, and has been cultivated for thousands of years.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albania has a long and ancient history of wine production, and belongs to the Old World of wine producing countries.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albania participated at the Olympic Games in 1972 for the first time.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The country made their Winter Olympic Games debut in 2006.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albania missed the next four games, two of them due to the 1980 and 1984 boycotts, but returned for the 1992 games in Barcelona.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Since then, Albania have participated in all games.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albania normally competes in events that include swimming, athletics, weightlifting, shooting and wrestling.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The country have been represented by the National Olympic Committee of Albania since 1972.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The nation has participated at the Mediterranean Games since the games of 1987 in Syria.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The Albanian athletes have won a total of 43 (8 gold, 17 silver and 18 bronze) medals from 1987 to 2013.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Popular sports in Albania include football, weightlifting, basketball, volleyball, tennis, swimming, rugby union and gymnastics.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Football is by far the most popular sport in Albania.
[src:albion/albania-p04] It is governed by the Football Association of Albania (Albanian: *Federata Shqiptare e Futbollit*, F.SH.F.), which has membership in FIFA and UEFA.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albania scored their first ever goal in a major tournament and secured their first ever win in European Championship when they beat Romania by 1–0 in a UEFA Euro 2016 match on 19 June 2016.
[src:albion/albania-p04] The most successful football clubs are Skënderbeu, KF Tirana, Dinamo Tirana, Partizani and Vllaznia.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Weightlifting is one of the most successful individual sports for the Albanians, with the national team winning medals at the European Weightlifting Championships and the rest international competitions.
[src:albion/albania-p04] Albanian weightlifters have won a total of 16 medals at the European Championships with one of them being gold, seven silver and eight bronze.
[src:albion/albania-p04] In the World Weightlifting Championships, the Albanian weightlifting team has won in 1972 a gold, in 2002 a silver, and in 2011 a bronze medal.
[src:albion/albina-mythology] The first mention of Albina is in the Anglo-Norman poem *Des Grantz Geanz*, which dates to the late 13th or early 14th century, and has been tentatively dated no later than 1333.
[src:albion/albina-mythology] An abridged form of the poem was appended as a prologue to the *Brut Chronicle*.
[src:albion/albina-mythology] In the poem, Albina and her 32 sisters are the daughters of Diosclesian, King of Syria.
[src:albion/albina-mythology] At a grand feast, they are wedded in arranged marriages to neighbouring kings.
[src:albion/albina-mythology] However, the women refuse to submit to their new husbands, believing themselves to be of nobler blood than they.
[src:albion/albina-mythology] At a second feast, Diosclesian chastises them for their disobedience, but Albina still refuses to comply with her father's orders of subservience.
[src:albion/albina-mythology] That night, she and her sisters murder their respective spouses.
[src:albion/albina-mythology] As punishment for their mass mariticide, the princesses are exiled to an uninhabited island, which Albina names Albion after herself.
[src:albion/albina-mythology] They survive by hunting and gathering, which is depicted as barbaric and a result of their fall from civilisation.
[src:albion/albina-mythology] Demons from hell then seduce them, and they give birth to a race of giants.
[src:albion/albina-mythology] The text identifies these giants as the ones that later Brutus of Troy encounters and slays when he arrives in Albion in Geoffrey of Monmouth's *Historia Regum Britanniae*, paving the way for permanent human settlement and the creation of the civilised Kingdom of Britain.
[src:albion/albion] The name for Scotland in most of the Celtic languages is related to Albion: *Alba* in Scottish Gaelic, *Albain* (genitive *Alban*) in Irish, *Nalbin* in Manx and *Alban* in Welsh and Cornish.
[src:albion/albion] These names were later Latinised as *Albania* and Anglicised as *Albany*, which were once alternative names for Scotland.
[src:albion/albion] The toponym in English is thought to derive from the Greek word Ἀλβίων mentioned by pseudo-Aristotle in *De Mundo*, Latinised as *Albiōn* (genitive *Albionis*).
[src:albion/albion] It is similarly mentioned by Ptolemy in his Geography and Pliny in the *Naturalis Historia*.
[src:albion/albion] The root **albiyo-* is also found in Gaulish and Galatian *albio-* 'world' and Welsh *elfydd* (Old Welsh *elbid* 'earth, world, land, country, district').
[src:albion/albion] It may be related to other European and Mediterranean toponyms such as *Alpes*, *Albania* or the river god Alpheus (originally 'whitish'). which has a possible etymology in the Proto-Indo-European word **albʰo-* 'white' (cf.
[src:albion/albion] The derivation from a word for 'white' is thought to refer perhaps to the white Cliffs of Dover in the southeast, visible from mainland Europe and a landmark at the narrowest crossing point.
[src:albion/albion] On the other hand, Celtic linguist Xavier Delamarre argued that it originally meant 'the world above, the visible world', in opposition to 'the world below', i.e. the underworld.
[src:albion/albion] 320 BC), as directly or indirectly quoted in the surviving excerpts of his works in later writers, speaks of *Albiōn and Iernē* (Great Britain and Ireland).
[src:albion/albion] Pytheas's grasp of the νῆσος Πρεττανική (*nēsos Prettanikē*, "Prettanic island") is somewhat blurry, and appears to include anything he considers a western island, including *Thule*.
[src:albion/albion] The name *Albion* was used by Isidore of Charax (1st century BC – 1st century AD) and subsequently by many classical writers.
[src:albion/albion] By the 1st century AD, the name refers unequivocally to Great Britain.
[src:albion/albion] But this "enigmatic name for Britain, revived much later by Romantic poets like William Blake, did not remain popular among Greek writers.
[src:albion/albion] It was soon replaced by Πρεττανία (*Prettanía*) and Βρεττανία (*Brettanía* 'Britain'), Βρεττανός (*Brettanós* 'Briton'), and Βρεττανικός (*Brettanikós*, meaning the adjective British).
[src:albion/albion] From these words the Romans derived the Latin forms Britannia, Britannus, and Britannicus respectively".
[src:albion/albion] ἐν τούτῳ γε μὴν νῆσοι μέγισται τυγχάνουσιν οὖσαι δύο, Βρεττανικαὶ λεγόμεναι, Ἀλβίων καὶ Ἰέρνη, τῶν προϊστορημένων μείζους, ὑπὲρ τοὺς Κελτοὺς κείμεναι.
[src:albion/albion] There are two very large islands in it, called the British Isles, Albion and Ierne; they are larger than those already mentioned, and lie beyond the land of the Celts.
[src:albion/albion] Pliny the Elder, in the fourth book of his *Natural History* (Latin: *Naturalis historia*) likewise calls Great Britain *Albion*.
[src:albion/albion] He begins his chapter on the British Isles (Latin: *Britanniae*, lit.
[src:albion/albion] Ex adverso huius situs Britannia insula clara Graecis nostrisque monimentis inter septentrionem et occidentem iacet, Germaniae, Galliae, Hispaniae, multo maximis Europae partibus magno intervallo adversa.
[src:albion/albion] Albion ipsi nomen fuit, cum Britanniae vocarentur omnes de quibus mox paulo dicemus.
[src:albion/albion] Opposite to this region lies the island of Britain, famous in the Greek records and in our own; it lies to the north-west, facing, across a wide channel, Germany, Gaul and Spain, countries which constitute by far the greater part of Europe.
[src:albion/albion] It was itself named Albion, while all the islands about which we shall soon briefly speak were called the Britains.
[src:albion/albion] In his 2nd century *Geography*, Ptolemy uses the name Ἀλουΐων (*Alouiōn*, "Albion") instead of the Roman name *Britannia*, possibly following the commentaries of Marinus of Tyre.
[src:albion/albion] He calls both Albion and Ierne in Ancient Greek: νῆσοι Βρεττανικαὶ, romanized: *nēsoi Brettanikai*, lit.
[src:albion/albion] In 930, the English king Æthelstan used the title *rex et primicerius totius Albionis regni*, 'king and chief of the whole realm of Albion'.
[src:albion/albion] His nephew, Edgar the Peaceful, styled himself in 970: *totius Albionis imperator augustus*, 'august emperor of all Albion'.
[src:albion/albion] A legend exists in various forms that giants were either the original inhabitants, or the founders of the land named Albion.
[src:albion/albion] After many adventures, Brutus and his fellow Trojans escape from Gaul and "set sail with a fair wind towards the promised island".
[src:albion/albion] "The island was then called Albion, and inhabited by none but a few giants.
[src:albion/albion] Geoffrey goes on to recount how the last of the giants are defeated, the largest one called Goëmagot is flung over a cliff by Corineus.
[src:albion/albion] The 13th century Prose *Merlin* drew on Geoffrey's story, but instead had Brutus and Corneus as two barons of Troy, who fled the city after its destruction.
[src:albion/albion] Brutus went to Britain and founded London, while Corneus, who was descended from giants, went to Britanny, where he founded cities and castles, and gave his name to Cornouaille.
[src:albion/albion] In this version the giants were descended from Corneus, and survived until the time of King Arthur, when they fought alongside the Saracens against the Britons during the Saxon invasion of Britain.
[src:albion/albion] Later, in the 14th century, a more elaborate tale was developed, claiming that Albina and her sisters founded Albion and procreated there a race of giants.
[src:albion/albion] The "Albina story" survives in several forms, including the octosyllabic Anglo-Norman poem "Des grantz geanz" dating to 1300–1334.
[src:albion/albion] According to the poem, in the 3970th year of the creation of the world, a king of Greece married his thirty daughters into royalty, but the haughty brides colluded to eliminate their husbands so they would be subservient to no one.
[src:albion/albion] The youngest would not be party to the crime and divulged the plot, so the other princesses were confined to an unsteerable rudderless ship and set adrift, and after three days reached an uninhabited land later to be known as "Britain".
[src:albion/albion] The eldest daughter Albina (*Albine*) was the first to step ashore and lay claim to the land, naming it after herself.
[src:albion/albion] At first, the women gathered acorns and fruits, but once they learned to hunt and obtain meat, it aroused their lecherous desires.
[src:albion/albion] As no other humans inhabited the land, they mated with evil spirits called "incubi", and subsequently with the sons they begot, engendering a race of giants.
[src:albion/albion] These giants are evidenced by huge bones which are unearthed.
[src:albion/albion] Brutus arrived 260 years after Albina, 1136 before the birth of Christ, but by then there were only 24 giants left, due to inner strife.
[src:albion/albion] As with Geoffrey of Monmouth's version, Brutus's band subsequently overtake the land, defeating Gogmagog in the process.
[src:albion/albion] The octosyllabic poem appears as a prologue to 16 out of 26 manuscripts of the Short Version of the Anglo-Norman prose *Brut*, which derives from Wace.
[src:albion/albion] Octosyllabic is not the only form the Anglo-Norman *Des Grantz Geanz*, there are five forms, the others being: the alexandrine, prose, short verse, and short prose versions.
[src:albion/albion] The Latin adaptation of the Albina story, *De Origine Gigantum*, appeared soon afterwards, in the 1330s.
[src:albion/albion] It has been edited by Carey & Crick (1995), and translated by Ruth Evans (1998).
[src:albion/albion] A variant tale occurs in the Middle English prose *Brut* (Brie ed., *The Brut or the Chronicles of England* 1906–1908) of the 14th century, an English rendition of the Anglo-Norman *Brut* deriving from Wace.
[src:albion/albion] In the Prolog of this chronicle, it was King "Dioclician" of "Surrey" (Syria), who had 33 daughters, the eldest being called "Albyne".
[src:albion/albion] The princesses are all banished to Albion after plotting to murder their husbands, where they couple with the local demons; their offspring became a race of giants.
[src:albion/albion] The chronicle asserts that during the voyage Albyne entrusted the fate of the sisters to "Appolyn", which was the god of their faith.
[src:albion/albion] The Syrian king who was her father sounds much like a Roman emperor, though Diocletian (3rd century) would be anachronistic, and Holinshed explains this as a bungling of the legend of Danaus and his fifty daughters who founded Argos.
[src:albion/albion] Because Geoffrey of Monmouth's work was regarded as fact until the late 17th century, the story appears in most early histories of Britain.
[src:albion/albion] Wace, Layamon, Raphael Holinshed, William Camden and John Milton repeat the legend and it appears in Edmund Spenser's *The Faerie Queene*.
[src:albion/albion] William Blake's poems *Milton* and *Jerusalem* feature Albion as an archetypal giant representing humanity.
[src:albion/albion] In 2010, artist Mark Sheeky donated the 2008 painting *Two Roman Legionaries Discovering The God-King Albion Turned Into Stone* to the Grosvenor Museum collection.
[src:albion/alexandrine] However, no tradition remains this simple.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Each applies additional constraints (such as obligatory stress or nonstress on certain syllables) and options (such as a permitted or required additional syllable at the end of one or both hemistichs).
[src:albion/alexandrine] Thus a line that is metrical in one tradition may be unmetrical in another.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Where the alexandrine has been adopted, it has frequently served as the heroic verse form of that language or culture, English being a notable exception.
[src:albion/alexandrine] The term "alexandrine" may be used with greater or lesser rigour.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Peureux suggests that only French syllabic verse with a 6+6 structure is, strictly speaking, an alexandrine.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Baïf is often credited with the reintroduction of the alexandrine in the mid-16th century.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Although alexandrines occurred in French verse as early as the 12th century, they were slightly looser rhythmically, and vied with the *décasyllabe* and *octosyllabe* for cultural prominence and use in various genres.
[src:albion/alexandrine] "The alexandrine came into its own in the middle of the sixteenth century with the poets of the Pléiade and was firmly established in the seventeenth century." It became the preferred line for the prestigious genres of epic and tragedy.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Classical alexandrines are always rhymed, often in couplets alternating masculine rhymes and feminine rhymes, though other configurations (such as quatrains and sonnets) are also common.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Victor Hugo began the process of loosening the strict two-hemistich structure.
[src:albion/alexandrine] The Symbolists further weakened the classical structure, sometimes eliminating any or all of these caesurae.
[src:albion/alexandrine] However, at no point did the newer line *replace* the older; rather, they were used concurrently, often in the same poem.
[src:albion/alexandrine] This loosening process eventually led to *vers libéré* and finally to *vers libre*.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Spenser added one alexandrine to his iambic pentameter stanza; Drayton composed the longest work entirely in English alexandrines.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Whereas the French alexandrine is syllabic, the English is accentual-syllabic; and the central caesura (a defining feature of the French) is not always rigidly preserved in English.
[src:albion/alexandrine] During the Middle Ages they typically occurred with heptameters (seven-beat lines), both exhibiting metrical looseness.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Around the mid-16th century stricter alexandrines were popular as the first line of poulter's measure couplets, fourteeners (strict iambic heptameters) providing the second line.
[src:albion/alexandrine] The Faerie Queene by Edmund Spenser, with its stanzas of eight iambic pentameter lines followed by one alexandrine, exemplifies what came to be its chief role: as a somewhat infrequent variant line in an otherwise iambic pentameter context.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Alexandrines provide occasional variation in the blank verse of William Shakespeare and his contemporaries (but rarely; they constitute only about 1% of Shakespeare's blank verse).
[src:albion/alexandrine] John Dryden and his contemporaries and followers likewise occasionally employed them as the second (rarely the first) line of heroic couplets, or even more distinctively as the third line of a triplet.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Then at the last and only couplet fraught With some unmeaning thing they call a thought, A needless Alexandrine ends the song, That, like a wounded snake, drags its slow length along.
[src:albion/alexandrine] The Spanish *verso alejandrino* is a line of 7+7 syllables, probably developed in imitation of the French alexandrine.
[src:albion/alexandrine] It was used beginning about 1200 for *mester de clerecía* (clerical verse), typically occurring in the *cuaderna vía*, a stanza of four *alejandrinos* all with a single end-rhyme.
[src:albion/alexandrine] The *alejandrino* was most prominent during the 13th and 14th centuries, after which time it was eclipsed by the metrically more flexible *arte mayor*.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Juan Ruiz's Book of Good Love is one of the best-known examples of *cuaderna vía*, though other verse forms also appear in the work.
[src:albion/alexandrine] The mid-16th-century poet Jan van der Noot pioneered syllabic Dutch alexandrines on the French model, but within a few decades Dutch alexandrines had been transformed into strict iambic hexameters with a caesura after the third foot.
[src:albion/alexandrine] From the Low Countries the accentual-syllabic alexandrine spread to other continental literatures.
[src:albion/alexandrine] The alexandrine (strictly iambic with a consistent medial caesura) became the dominant long line of the German baroque.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Though looser instances of this (nominally) 13-syllable line were occasionally used in Polish literature, it was Mikołaj Rej and Jan Kochanowski who, in the 16th century, introduced the syllabically strict line as a vehicle for major works.
[src:albion/alexandrine] The Czech alexandrine is a comparatively recent development, based on the French alexandrine and introduced by Karel Hynek Mácha in the 19th century.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Its structure forms a halfway point between features usual in syllabic and in accentual-syllabic verse, being more highly constrained than most syllabic verse, and less so than most accentual-syllabic verse.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Hungarian metrical verse may be written either syllabically (the older and more traditional style, known as "national") or quantitatively.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Although deriving from native folk versification, it is possible that this line, and the related 6-syllable line, were influenced by Latin or Romance examples.
[src:albion/alexandrine] When employed in 4-line or 8-line stanzas and rhyming in couplets, this is called the Hungarian alexandrine; it is the Hungarian heroic verse form.
[src:albion/alexandrine] Beginning with the 16th-century verse of Bálint Balassi, this became the dominant Hungarian verse form.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] In Greek mythology, **Alpheus** or **Alpheios** (/ælˈfiːəs/; Ancient Greek: Ἀλφειός, lit.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] 'whitish') was the river god who embodied the river of the same name.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] Like most river gods, Alpheus was the child of the Titans Oceanus and his sister-wife Tethys.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] Telegone, daughter of Pharis, bore Alpheus' son, the king Orsilochus.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] Through Orsilochus, Alpheus became the grandfather of Diocles, and great-grandfather of a pair of soldiers, Crethon and Orsilochus, who were slain by Aeneas during the Trojan War.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] Alpheus was also called the father of Melantheia who became the mother of Eirene by Poseidon.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] In later accounts, Alpheus (**Alphionis**) was the father of Phoenissa, possible mother of Endymion by Zeus.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] The well of Arethusa is a symbol of Syracuse.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] Alpheus took on water form jumping into the stream, but the earth opened and the stream flew underground to appear in a bay near Syracuse, near the island Ortygia, a location sacred to Artemis.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] According to other traditions, Artemis herself was the object of the love of Alpheus.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] Once, it is said, when pursued by him she fled to Letrini in Elis, and here she covered her face and those of her companions (nymphs) with mud, so that Alpheus could not discover or distinguish her, and was obliged to return.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] This occasioned the building of a temple of Artemis Alphaea at Letrini.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] According to another version, the goddess fled to Ortygia, where she had likewise a temple under the name of Alphaea.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] An allusion to Alpheius' love of Artemis is also contained in the fact that at Olympia the two divinities had one altar in common.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] In these accounts two or more distinct stories seem to be mixed up together, but they probably originated in the popular belief that there was a natural subterranean communication between the river Alpheios and the well Arethusa.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] It was believed that a cup thrown into the Alpheus would make its reappearance in the well Arethusa in Ortygia.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] Plutarch gives an account which is altogether unconnected with those mentioned above.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] According to him, Alpheus was a son of Helios, and killed his brother Cercaphus in a contest.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] Haunted by despair and the Erinyes he leapt into the river Nyctimus which afterwards received the name Alpheus.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] Alpheus was also the river which Heracles, in the fifth of his labours, rerouted in order to clean the filth from the Augean Stables in a single day, a task which had been presumed to be impossible.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] Alpheus is often associated with Antinous, the lover of the Roman Emperor Hadrian.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] Antinous was a Greek youth who had drowned in the Nile River.
[src:albion/alpheus-deity] After he was deified, coins of the period depict him as Alpheios or Hadrian with Alpheios.
